# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dual-in-line-package
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dual-in-line-package/4000-series-integrated-circuits] The **4000 series** is a CMOS logic family of integrated circuits (ICs) first introduced in 1968 by RCA.
[src:dual-in-line-package/4000-series-integrated-circuits] It was slowly migrated into the 4000B buffered series after about 1975.
[src:dual-in-line-package/4000-series-integrated-circuits] It had a much wider supply voltage range than any contemporary logic family (3 V to 18 V recommended range for "B" series).
[src:dual-in-line-package/4000-series-integrated-circuits] Almost all IC manufacturers active during this initial era fabricated models for this series.
[src:dual-in-line-package/4000-series-integrated-circuits] Its naming convention is still in use today.
[src:dual-in-line-package/4000-series-integrated-circuits] The 4000 series was introduced as the *CD4000 COS/MOS* series in 1968 by RCA as a lower-power and more versatile alternative to the 7400 series of transistor-transistor logic (TTL) chips.
[src:dual-in-line-package/4000-series-integrated-circuits] The logic functions were implemented with the newly introduced complementary metal–oxide–semiconductor (CMOS) technology.
[src:dual-in-line-package/4000-series-integrated-circuits] While initially marketed with "COS/MOS" labeling by RCA (which stood for "complementary symmetry metal–oxide semiconductor"), the shorter *CMOS* terminology emerged as the industry preference to refer to the technology.
[src:dual-in-line-package/4000-series-integrated-circuits] The first chips in the series were designed by a group led by Albert Medwin.
[src:dual-in-line-package/4000-series-integrated-circuits] Wide adoption was initially hindered by the comparatively lower speeds of the designs compared to TTL-based designs.
[src:dual-in-line-package/4000-series-integrated-circuits] Speed limitations were eventually overcome with newer fabrication methods (such as self-aligned gates of polysilicon instead of metal).
[src:dual-in-line-package/4000-series-integrated-circuits] These CMOS variants performed on par with contemporary TTL.
[src:dual-in-line-package/4000-series-integrated-circuits] The series was extended in the late 1970s and 1980s with new models that were given 45xx and 45xxx designations, but are usually still regarded by engineers as part of the 4000 series.
[src:dual-in-line-package/4000-series-integrated-circuits] Texas Instruments) ported the 4000 series to newer HCMOS-based designs to provide greater speeds.
[src:dual-in-line-package/4000-series-integrated-circuits] The 4000 series facilitates simpler circuit design through relatively low power consumption, a wide range of supply voltages, and vastly increased load-driving capability (fanout) compared to TTL.
[src:dual-in-line-package/4000-series-integrated-circuits] This makes the series ideal for use in prototyping LSI designs.
[src:dual-in-line-package/4000-series-integrated-circuits] While TTL ICs are similarly modular, these usually lack the symmetrical drive strength of CMOS and may therefore require more consideration of the loads applied on its outputs.
[src:dual-in-line-package/4000-series-integrated-circuits] Just like with TTL, buffered models can drive higher electrical current (mainly available for I/O devices like octal latches and three-state drivers) but have a slightly higher risk of introducing ringing (transient oscillations), unless correctly damped or terminated.
[src:dual-in-line-package/4000-series-integrated-circuits] Many models contain a high level of integration, including fully integrated 7-segment display counters, walking ring counters, and full adders.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] The **MOS Technology 6502** is an 8-bit microprocessor that was designed by a small team led by Chuck Peddle for MOS Technology and was launched in September 1975.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] The design team had formerly worked at Motorola on the Motorola 6800 project; the 6502 is essentially a simplified, less expensive and faster version of that design using depletion-load NMOS technology that made using the microchip in computers much cheaper.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] When it was introduced, the 6502 was the least expensive microprocessor on the market by a considerable margin.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] It initially sold for less than one-sixth the cost of competing designs from larger companies, such as the 6800 or Intel 8080.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Its introduction caused rapid decreases in pricing across the entire processor market.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Along with the Zilog Z80, it sparked a series of projects that resulted in the home computer revolution of the early 1980s.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Home video game consoles and home computers of the 1970s through the early 1990s, such as the Atari 2600, Atari 8-bit computers, Apple II, Nintendo Entertainment System, Commodore 64, Atari Lynx, BBC Micro and others, use the 6502 or variations of the basic design.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Soon after the 6502's introduction, MOS Technology was purchased outright by Commodore International, who continued to sell the microprocessor and licenses to other manufacturers.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] In the early days of the 6502, it was second-sourced by Rockwell and Synertek, and later licensed to other companies.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] In 1981, the Western Design Center started development of a CMOS version, the 65C02.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] This continues to be widely used in embedded systems, with estimated production volumes in the hundreds of millions.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Motorola started the 6800 microprocessor project in 1971 with Tom Bennett as the main architect.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Bennett hired Chuck Peddle in 1973 to do architectural support work on the 6800 family products already in progress.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Bennett already was at work on what became the 6800.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] "He hired me," Peddle says of Bennett, "to do the architectural support work for the product he'd already started." … Peddle says.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] "Motorola tried to kill it several times.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Without Bennett, the 6800 would not have happened, and a lot of the industry would not have happened, either." Peddle contributed in many areas, including the design of the 6850 ACIA (serial interface).
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Peddle would accompany Motorola salespeople on customer visits, and found that customers were put off by the high cost of the microprocessor chips.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] At the same time, these visits invariably resulted in the engineers he presented to producing lists of required instructions that were much smaller than "all these fancy instructions" that had been included in the 6800.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Peddle and other team members started outlining the design of an improved feature, reduced-size microprocessor.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] At that time, Motorola's new semiconductor fabrication facility in Austin, Texas, was having difficulty producing MOS chips, and mid-1974 was the beginning of a year-long recession in the semiconductor industry.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Also, many of the Mesa, Arizona employees were displeased with the upcoming relocation to Austin.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Motorola's Semiconductor Products Division management showed no interest in Peddle's low-cost microprocessor proposal.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Eventually, Peddle was given an official letter telling him to stop working on the system.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Peddle responded to the order by informing Motorola that the letter represented an official declaration of "project abandonment", and as such, the intellectual property he had developed to that point was now his.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] The 6502 was designed by many of the same engineers that had designed the Motorola 6800 microprocessor family.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] In a November 1975 interview, Motorola's Chairman, Bob Galvin, ultimately agreed that Peddle's concept was a good one and that the division missed an opportunity, "We did not choose the right leaders in the Semiconductor Products division." The division was reorganized and the management replaced.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Peddle began looking outside Motorola for a source of funding for this new project.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Sevin later admitted this was because he was afraid Motorola would sue them.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] While Peddle was visiting Ford Motor Company on one of his sales trips, Bob Johnson, later head of Ford's engine automation division, mentioned that their former colleague John Paivinen had moved to General Instrument and taught himself semiconductor design.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Paivinen then formed MOS Technology in Valley Forge, Pennsylvania in 1969 with two other executives from General Instrument, Mort Jaffe and Don McLaughlin.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Allen-Bradley, a supplier of electronic components and industrial controls, acquired a majority interest in 1970.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] The company designed and fabricated custom ICs for customers and had developed a line of calculator chips.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] After the Mostek efforts fell through, Peddle approached Paivinen, who "immediately got it".
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] On 19 August 1974, Chuck Peddle, Bill Mensch, Rod Orgill, Harry Bawcom, Ray Hirt, Terry Holdt, and Wil Mathys left Motorola to join MOS.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Of the seventeen chip designers and layout people on the 6800 team, eight left.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] The goal of the team was to design and produce a low-cost microprocessor for embedded applications and to target as wide as possible a customer base.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] This would be possible only if the microprocessor was low cost, and the team set the price goal for volume purchases at $5.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Mensch later stated the goal was not the processor price itself, but to create a set of chips that could sell at $20 to compete with the recently introduced Intel 4040 that sold for $29 in a similar complete chipset.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Chips are produced by printing multiple copies of the chip design on the surface of a wafer, a thin disk of highly pure silicon.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Smaller chips can be printed in greater numbers on the same wafer, decreasing their relative price.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Additionally, wafers always include some number of tiny physical defects that are scattered across the surface.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Any chip printed in that location will fail and has to be discarded.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Smaller chips mean any single copy is less likely to be printed on a defect.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] For both of these reasons, the cost of the final product is strongly dependent on the size of the chip design.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] The original 6800 chips were intended to be 180 by 180 mils (4.6 mm × 4.6 mm), but layout was completed at 212 by 212 mils (5.4 mm × 5.4 mm), or an area of 29.0 mm2.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] For the new design, the cost goal demanded a size goal of 153 by 168 mils (3.9 mm × 4.3 mm), or an area of 16.6 mm2, roughly half that of the 6800.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Several new techniques would be needed to hit this goal.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Two significant advances arrived in the market just as the 6502 was being designed that provided significant cost reductions.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] The first was the move to depletion-load NMOS.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] The 6800 used an early NMOS process, enhancement mode, that required three supply voltages.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] One of the 6800's headlining features was an onboard voltage doubler that allowed a single +5 V supply be used for +5, −5 and +12 V internally, as opposed to other chips of the era like the Intel 8080 that required three separate supply pins.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] While this feature reduced the complexity of the power supply and pin layout, it still required separate power lines to the various gates on the chip, driving up complexity and size.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] By moving to the new depletion-load design, a single +5 V supply was all that was needed, eliminating all of this complexity.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] A further advantage was that depletion-load designs used less power while switching, thus running cooler and allowing higher operating speeds.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Another practical offshoot is that the clock signal for earlier CPUs had to be strong enough to survive all the dissipation as it traveled through the circuits, which almost always required a separate external chip that could supply a powerful signal.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] With the reduced power requirements of depletion-load design, the clock could be moved onto the chip, simplifying the overall computer design.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] These changes greatly reduced complexity and the cost of implementing a complete system.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] A wider change taking place in the industry was the introduction of projection masking.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Previously, chips were patterned onto the surface of the wafer by placing a mask on the surface of the wafer and then shining a bright light on it.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] The masks often picked up tiny bits of dirt or photoresist as they were lifted off the chip, causing flaws in those locations on any subsequent masking.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] With complex designs like CPUs, 5 or 6 such masking steps would be used, and the chance that at least one of these steps would introduce a flaw was very high.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] In most cases, 90% of such designs were flawed, resulting in a 10% yield.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] The price of the working examples had to cover the production cost of the 90% that were thrown away.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] In 1973, Perkin-Elmer introduced the Micralign system, which projected an image of the mask on the wafer instead of requiring direct contact.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Masks no longer picked up dirt from the wafers and lasted on the order of 100,000 uses rather than 10.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] This eliminated step-to-step failures and the high flaw rates formerly seen on complex designs.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Yields on CPUs immediately jumped from 10% to 60 or 70%.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] This meant the price of the CPU declined roughly the same amount and the microprocessor suddenly became a commodity device.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] MOS Technology's existing fabrication lines were based on the older PMOS technology, they had not yet begun to work with NMOS when the team arrived.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Paivinen promised to have an NMOS line up and running in time to begin the production of the new CPU.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] He delivered on the promise, the new line was ready by June 1975.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Chuck Peddle, Rod Orgill, and Wil Mathys designed the initial architecture of the new processors.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] The main change in terms of chip size was the elimination of the tri-state drivers from the address bus outputs.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] A three-state bus has states for *1*, *0* and *high impedance*.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] The last state is used to allow other devices to access the bus, and is typically used for multiprocessing, or more commonly in these roles, for direct memory access (DMA).
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] While useful, this feature is expensive in terms of on-chip circuitry.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] The 6502 simply removed this feature, in keeping with its design as an inexpensive controller being used for specific tasks and communicating with simple devices.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Peddle suggested that anyone who required this style of access could implement it with a 74158.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] The next major difference was to simplify the registers.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] To start with, one of the two accumulators was removed.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] General-purpose registers like accumulators have to be accessed by many parts of the instruction decoder, and thus require significant amounts of wiring to move data to and from their storage.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Two accumulators makes many coding tasks easier but costs the chip design itself significant complexity.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Further savings were made by reducing the stack register from 16 to 8 bits, meaning that the stack could only be 256 bytes long, which was enough for its intended role as a microcontroller.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] The 16-bit IX index register was split in two, becoming X and Y.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] More importantly, the style of access changed.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] In the 6800, IX held a 16-bit address which was offset by an 8-bit number stored with the instruction and added to the address.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] In the 6502 (and most other contemporary designs), the 16-bit base address was stored in the instruction, and the 8-bit X or Y was added to it.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Finally, the instruction set was simplified, simplifying the decoder and control logic.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Of the original 72 instructions in the 6800, 56 were implemented.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Among those removed were instructions that operated between the 6800's two accumulators, and several branch instructions inspired by the PDP-11.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] The chip's high-level design had to be turned into drawings of transistors and interconnects.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] At MOS Technology, the layout was a very manual process done with colored pencils and vellum paper.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] The layout consisted of thousands of polygon shapes on six different drawings; one for each layer of the fabrication process.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Given the size limits, the entire chip design had to be constantly considered.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Mensch and Paivinen worked on the instruction decoder while Mensch, Peddle and Orgill worked on the ALU and registers.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] A further advance, developed at a party, was a way to share some of the internal wiring to allow the ALU to be reduced in size.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Despite their best efforts, the final design ended up being larger than the original target.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] The original version of the processor had no rotate right (ROR) capability, so the instruction was omitted from the original documentation.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] The next iteration of the design shrank the chip and added the rotate right capability, and ROR was included in revised documentation.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] MOS would introduce two microprocessors based on the same underlying design: the 6501 would plug into the same socket as the Motorola 6800, while the 6502 re-arranged the pinout to support an on-chip clock oscillator.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Both would work with other support chips designed for the 6800.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] They would not run 6800 software because they had a different instruction set, different registers, and mostly different addressing modes.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Rod Orgill was responsible for the 6501 design; he had assisted John Buchanan at Motorola on the 6800.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Bill Mensch did the 6502; he was the designer of the 6820 PIA at Motorola.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Harry Bawcom, Mike Janes and Sydney-Anne Holt helped with the layout.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] MOS Technology's microprocessor introduction was different from the traditional months-long product launch.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] The first run of a new integrated circuit is normally used for internal testing and shared with select customers as engineering samples.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] These chips often have minor design defects that will be corrected before production begins.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Chuck Peddle's goal was to sell the first run 6501 and 6502 chips to the attendees at the Western Electronics Show and Convention (WESCON) in San Francisco beginning on September 16, 1975.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Peddle was a very effective spokesman and the MOS Technology microprocessors were extensively covered in the trade press.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] One of the earliest was a full-page story on the MCS6501 and MCS6502 microprocessors in the July 24, 1975 issue of *Electronics* magazine.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Advertisements for the 6501 appeared in several publications the first week of August 1975.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] The 6501 would be for sale at WESCON for $20 each.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] In September 1975, the advertisements included both the 6501 and the 6502 microprocessors.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] When MOS Technology arrived at WESCON, they found that exhibitors were not permitted to sell anything on the show floor.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] They rented the MacArthur Suite at the St.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Francis Hotel and directed customers there to purchase the processors.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] At the suite, the processors were stored in large jars to imply that the chips were in production and readily available.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] The customers did not know the bottom half of each jar contained non-functional chips.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] The chips were $20 and $25 while the documentation package was an additional $10.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Users were encouraged to make photocopies of the documents, an inexpensive way for MOS Technology to distribute product information.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] The preliminary data sheets listed just 55 instructions and excluded the Rotate Right (ROR) instruction, which was not supported on these early chips.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] The reviews in *Byte* and *EDN* noted the lack of the ROR instruction.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] The next revision of the layout fixed this problem and the May 1976 datasheet listed 56 instructions.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Peddle wanted every interested engineer and hobbyist to have access to the chips and documentation, whereas other semiconductor companies only wanted to deal with "serious" customers.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] For example, Signetics was introducing the 2650 microprocessor and its advertisements asked readers to write for information on their company letterhead.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] The 6501/6502 introduction in print and at WESCON was a success.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] The press coverage got Motorola's attention, precipitating pricing adjustments and lawsuits.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] In October 1975, Motorola reduced the price of a single 6800 microprocessor from $175 to $69.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] The $300 system design kit was reduced to $150 and it now came with a printed circuit board.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] On November 3, 1975, Motorola sought an injunction in Federal Court to stop MOS Technology from making and selling microprocessor products.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] They also filed a lawsuit claiming patent infringement and misappropriation of trade secrets.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Motorola claimed that seven former employees joined MOS Technology to create that company's microprocessor products.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Motorola was a billion-dollar company with a plausible case and expensive lawyers.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] On October 30, 1974, Motorola had filed numerous patent applications on the microprocessor family and was granted twenty-five patents.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] The first was in June 1976 and the second was to Bill Mensch on July 6, 1976, for the 6820 PIA chip layout.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] These patents covered the 6800 bus and how the peripheral chips interfaced with the microprocessor.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Motorola began making transistors in 1950 and had a portfolio of semiconductor patents.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Allen-Bradley decided not to fight this case and sold their interest in MOS Technology back to the founders.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Four of the former Motorola engineers were named in the suit: Chuck Peddle, Will Mathys, Bill Mensch and Rod Orgill.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] All were named inventors in the 6800 patent applications.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] During the discovery process, Motorola found that one engineer, Mike Janes, had ignored Peddle's instructions and brought his 6800 design documents to MOS Technology.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] In March 1976, the now independent MOS Technology was running out of money and had to settle the case.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] They agreed to drop the 6501 processor, pay Motorola $200,000 and return the documents that Motorola contended were confidential.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Both companies agreed to cross-license microprocessor patents.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] That May, Motorola dropped the price of a single 6800 microprocessor to $35.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] By November, Commodore had acquired MOS Technology.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] With legal troubles behind them, MOS was still left with the problem of getting developers to try their processor, prompting Chuck Peddle to design the MDT650 development system.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Another group inside the company designed the KIM-1, which was sold semi-complete and could be turned into a usable system with the addition of a 3rd party computer terminal and compact cassette drive.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] While it sold well to its intended market, the company found the KIM-1 also sold well to hobbyists and tinkerers.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] The related Rockwell AIM-65 control, training, and development system also did well.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] The software in the AIM 65 was based on that in the MDT.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Another roughly similar product was the Synertek SYM-1.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] One of the first external uses for the design was the Apple I microcomputer, introduced in 1976.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] The 6502 was next used in the Commodore PET and Apple II, both released in 1977.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] It was later used in the Atari 8-bit computers, Acorn Atom, BBC Micro, VIC-20 and other designs both for home computers and business, such as Ohio Scientific and Oric computers.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] The 6510, a direct successor of the 6502 with a digital I/O port and a tri-state address bus, was the CPU utilized in the best-selling Commodore 64 home computer.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Another important use of the 6500 family was in video games.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] The first to make use of the processor design was the 1977 Atari VCS, later renamed the Atari 2600.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] The VCS used a 6502 variant named the 6507, which had fewer pins, so it could address only 8 KB of memory.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Millions of the Atari consoles would be sold, each with a MOS processor.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Another significant use was by the Nintendo Entertainment System (NES) and Famicom.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] The 6502 used in the NES was a second source version by Ricoh, a partial system on a chip, that lacked the binary-coded decimal mode but added 22 memory-mapped registers and on-die hardware for sound generation, joypad reading, and sprite list DMA.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Called 2A03 in NTSC consoles and 2A07 in PAL consoles, this processor was produced exclusively for Nintendo.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] 6502 or variants were used in all of Commodore's floppy disk drives for all of their 8-bit computers, from the PET line through the Commodore 128D, including the Commodore 64.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] 8-inch PET drives had two 6502 processors.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Atari used the same 6507 used in the Atari 2600 for its 810 and 1050 disk drives used for all of their 8-bit computer line, from the 400/800 through the XEGS.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] In the 1980s, a popular electronics magazine Elektor used the processor in its microprocessor development board Junior Computer.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] The CMOS successor to the 6502, the WDC 65C02, also saw use in home computers and video game consoles.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Apple used it in the Apple II line, starting with the Apple IIc and later variants of the Apple IIe, and also offered a kit to upgrade older IIe systems with the new processor.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] The Hudson Soft HuC6280 chip used in the TurboGrafx-16 was based on a 65C02 core.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] The Atari Lynx used a custom chip named "Mikey" designed by Epyx which included a VLSI VL65NC02 licensed cell.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] The G65SC12 by GTE Microcircuits (renamed California Micro Devices) variant was used in the BBC Master.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Some models of the BBC Master also included an additional G65SC102 co-processor.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] The 6502 is a little-endian 8-bit processor with a 16-bit address bus.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] The original versions were fabricated using an 8 µm process technology with a die size of 3.9 mm × 4.3 mm (153 by 168 mils), for a total area of 16.6 mm2.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] The internal logic runs at the same speed as the external clock rate.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] It featured a simple two-stage pipeline; on each cycle, the processor fetches one byte from memory and processes another.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] This means that any single instruction can take as few as two cycles to complete, depending on the number of operands that instruction uses.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] For comparison, the Zilog Z80 required two cycles to fetch memory, and the minimum instruction time was four cycles.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Thus, despite the lower clock speeds compared to competing designs, typically in the neighborhood of 1 to 2 MHz, the 6502's performance was competitive with CPUs using significantly faster clocks.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] This is partly due to a simple state machine implemented by combinational (clockless) logic to a greater extent than in many other designs; the two-phase clock (supplying two synchronizations per cycle) could thereby control the machine cycle directly.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] This design also led to one useful design note of the 6502, and the 6800 before it.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Because the chip only accessed memory during a certain part of the clock cycle, other chips in a system could access memory during those times when the 6502 was off the bus.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] This was sometimes known as *hidden access*.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] This technique was widely used by computer systems; they would use memory capable of access at 2 MHz, and then run the CPU at 1 MHz.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] This guaranteed that the CPU and video hardware could interleave their accesses, with a total performance matching that of the memory device.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Because this access was every other cycle, there was no need to signal the CPU to avoid using the bus, making this sort of access easy to implement without any bus logic.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] When faster memories became available in the 1980s, newer machines could use this same technique while running at higher clock rates; the BBC Micro used newer RAM that allowed its CPU to run at 2 MHz while still using the same bus sharing techniques.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Like most simple CPUs of the era, the dynamic NMOS 6502 chip is not sequenced by microcode but decoded directly using a dedicated PLA.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] The decoder occupied about 15% of the chip area.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] This compares to later microcode-based designs like the Motorola 68000, where the microcode ROM and decoder engine represented about a third of the gates in the system.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Like its precursor, the 6800, the 6502 has very few registers.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] This compares to a contemporaneous competitor, the Intel 8080, which likewise has one 8-bit accumulator and a 16-bit program counter, but has six more general-purpose 8-bit registers (which can be combined into three 16-bit pointers) and a larger 16-bit stack pointer.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] In order to make up somewhat for the lack of registers, the 6502 includes a *zero page* addressing mode that uses one address byte in the instruction instead of the two needed to address the full 64 KB of memory.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] This provides fast access to the first 256 bytes of RAM by using shorter instructions.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] For instance, an instruction to add a value from memory to the value in the accumulator would normally be three bytes, one for the instruction and two for the 16-bit address.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Using the zero page reduces this to an 8-bit address, reducing the total instruction length to two bytes, and thus improving instruction performance.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Software access to the stack is done via four implied addressing mode instructions, whose functions are to push or pop (pull) the accumulator or the processor status register.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] The same stack is also used for subroutine calls via the JSR (jump to subroutine) and RTS (return from subroutine) instructions and for interrupt handling.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] On some 6502-based microcomputers with an operating system, the operating system uses most of the zero page, leaving only a handful of locations for the user.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Addressing modes also include *implied* (1-byte instructions); *absolute* (3 bytes); *indexed absolute* (3 bytes); *indexed zero-page* (2 bytes); *relative* (2 bytes); *accumulator* (1); *indirect,x* and *indirect,y* (2); and *immediate* (2).
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Accumulator mode operates on the accumulator register and does not need any operand data.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Immediate mode uses an 8-bit literal operand.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] The indirect modes are useful for array processing and pointer-based data structures.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] With the 5 or 6 cycle *indirect,y* mode, the 8-bit Y register is added to a 16-bit base address read from zero page, which is located by a single byte following the opcode.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] The Y register is therefore an *index* register in the sense that it is used to hold an actual *index*.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Incrementing the index register to walk the array byte-wise takes only two additional cycles.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] With the less frequently used *indirect,x* mode, the effective address for the operation is found at the zero page address formed by adding the second byte of the instruction to the contents of the X register.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Using the indexed modes, the zero page effectively acts as a set of up to 128 additional (low-performance) address registers.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] The 6502 is capable of performing addition and subtraction in binary or binary-coded decimal.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Placing the CPU into BCD mode with the `SED` (set D flag) instruction results in decimal arithmetic, in which `$99 + $01` would result in *$00* and the carry (C) flag being set.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] In binary mode, entered with `CLD` (clear D flag), the same operation would result in *$9A* and the carry flag being cleared.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Other than Atari BASIC, BCD mode was seldom used in home-computer applications.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] 6502 instruction operation codes (*opcodes*) are 8 bits long and have the general form AAABBBCC, where AAA and CC define the opcode, and BBB defines the addressing mode.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] For example, the `ORA` instruction performs a bitwise OR on the bits in the accumulator with another value.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] The instruction opcode is of the form 000BBB01, where BBB may be 010 for an immediate mode value (constant), 001 for zero-page fixed address, 011 for an absolute address, and so on.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] This pattern is not universal, as there are exceptions, but it allows opcode values to be easily converted to assembly mnemonics for the majority of instructions, handling the edge cases with special-purpose code.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Of the 256 possible opcodes available using an 8-bit pattern, the original 6502 uses 151 of them, organized into 56 instructions with (possibly) multiple addressing modes.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Depending on the instruction and addressing mode, the opcode may require zero, one or two additional bytes for operands.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Hence 6502 machine instructions vary in length from one to three bytes.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] The operand is stored in the 6502's customary little-endian format.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Each CPU machine instruction takes up a certain number of clock cycles, usually equal to the number of memory accesses.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] For example, the absolute indexing mode of the ORA instruction takes 4 clock cycles; 3 cycles to read the instruction and 1 cycle to read the value of the absolute address.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] If no memory is accessed, the number of clock cycles is two.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] The minimum clock cycles for any instruction is two.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] When using indexed addressing, if the result crosses a page boundary an extra clock cycle is added.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Also, when a zero page address is used in indexing mode (e.g. zp,X) an extra clock cycle is added.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] The 65C816, the 16-bit CMOS descendant of the 6502, also supports 24-bit addressing, which results in instructions being assembled with three-byte operands, also arranged in little-endian format.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] The remaining 105 opcodes are undefined.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] In the original design, instructions where the low-order 4 bits (*nibble*) were 3, 7, B or F were not used, providing room for future expansion.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Likewise, the $x2 column had only a single entry, `LDX #*constant*`.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] The remaining 25 empty slots were distributed.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Some of the empty slots were used in the 65C02 to provide both new instructions and variations on existing ones with new addressing modes.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] The $xF instructions were initially left free to allow 3rd-party vendors to add their own instructions, but later versions of the 65C02 standardized a set of bit manipulation instructions developed by Rockwell Semiconductor.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] A 6502 assembly language statement consists of a three-character instruction mnemonic, followed by any operands.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Instructions that do not take a separate operand but target a single register based on the addressing mode combine the target register in the instruction mnemonic, so the assembler uses `INX` as opposed to `INC X` to increment the X register.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] are undefined in the 6502 instruction set.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] The following 6502 assembly language source code is for a subroutine named `TOLOWER`, which copies a null-terminated character string from one location to another, converting upper-case letter characters to lower-case letters.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] The string being copied is the "source", and the string into which the converted source is stored is the "destination".
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] The processor's non-maskable interrupt (NMI) input is edge sensitive, which means that the interrupt is triggered by the falling edge of the signal rather than its level.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Consequently a wired-OR interrupt circuit cannot be readily supported.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] However, this also prevents nested NMI interrupts from occurring until the interrupt source hardware makes the NMI input inactive again, often under control of the NMI interrupt handler.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] The simultaneous assertion of the NMI and IRQ (maskable) hardware interrupt lines causes IRQ to be ignored.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] However, if the IRQ line remains asserted after the servicing of the NMI, the processor will almost immediately respond to IRQ, as IRQ is level sensitive.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] Thus a sort of built-in interrupt priority was established in the 6502 design.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] The B flag is set by the 6502's periodically sampling its NMI edge detector's output and its IRQ input.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] The IRQ signal being driven low is only recognized though if IRQs are not masked by the I flag.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] If in this way a NMI request or (maskable) IRQ is detected the B flag is set to zero and causes the processor to execute the BRK instruction next instead of executing the next instruction based on the program counter.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] The BRK instruction then pushes the processor status onto the stack, with the B flag bit set to zero.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] At the end of its execution the BRK instruction resets the B flag's value to one.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] This is the only way the B flag can be modified.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] If an instruction other than the BRK instruction pushes the B flag onto the stack as part of the processor status the B flag always has the value one.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] A high-to-low transition on the SO input pin will set the processor's overflow status bit.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] This can be used for fast response to external hardware.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] For example, a high-speed polling device driver can poll the hardware once in only three cycles using a Branch-on-oVerflow-Clear (`BVC`) instruction that branches to itself until overflow is set by an SO falling transition.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] The Commodore 1541 and other Commodore floppy disk drives use this technique to detect when the serializer is ready to transfer another byte of disk data.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p01] The system hardware and software design must ensure that an SO will not occur during arithmetic processing and disrupt calculations.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p02] The 6502 was the most prolific variant of the 65xx series family from MOS Technology.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p02] The 6501 and 6502 have 40-pin DIP packages; the 6503, 6504, 6505, and 6507 are 28-pin DIP versions, for reduced chip and circuit board cost.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p02] In all of the 28-pin versions, the pin count is reduced by leaving off some of the high-order address pins and various combinations of function pins, making those functions unavailable.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p02] The omission of four address pins reduces the external addressability to 4 KB (from the 64 KB of the 6502), though the internal PC register and all effective address calculations remain 16-bit.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p02] The 6507 omits both interrupt pins in order to include address line A12, providing 8 KB of external addressability but no interrupt capability.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p02] One popular 6502-based computer, the Commodore 64, used a modified 6502 CPU, the 6510.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p02] Unlike the 6503–6505 and 6507, the 6510 is a 40-pin chip that adds internal hardware: a 6-bit parallel I/O port mapped to addresses 0000 and 0001.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p02] The 6508 is another chip that, like the 6510, adds internal hardware: 256 bytes of SRAM and an 8-bit I/O port similar to those featured by the 6510.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p02] Though these chips do not have reduced pin counts compared to the 6502, they need new pins for the added parallel I/O port.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p02] In this case, no address lines are among the removed pins.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p02] The Western Design Center designed and, as of 2025, still produces the WDC 65C816S processor, a 16-bit, static-core successor to the 65C02.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p02] The W65C816S is a newer variant of the 65C816, which is the core of the Apple IIGS computer and is the basis of the Ricoh 5A22 processor that powers the Super Nintendo Entertainment System.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p02] The W65C816S incorporates minor improvements over the 65C816 that make the newer chip not an exact hardware-compatible replacement for the earlier one.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p02] Among these improvements was conversion to a static core, which makes it possible to stop the clock in either phase without the registers losing data.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p02] Available through electronics distributors, as of March 2020, the W65C816S is officially rated for 14 MHz operation.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p02] The Western Design Center also designed and produced the 65C802, which was a 65C816 core with a 64-kilobyte address space in a 65(C)02 pin-compatible package.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p02] The 65C802 could be retrofitted to a 6502 board and would function as a 65C02 on power-up, operating in "emulation mode." As with the 65C816, a two-instruction sequence would switch the 65C802 to "native mode" operation, exposing its 16-bit accumulator and index registers, and other 65C816 features.
[src:dual-in-line-package/6502-p02] The 65C802 was not widely used and production ended.
[src:dual-in-line-package/80286] The Intel **80286** (also marketed as the **iAPX 286** and often called **Intel 286**) is a 16-bit microprocessor that was introduced on February 1, 1982.
[src:dual-in-line-package/80286] It was the first 8086-based CPU with separate, non-multiplexed address and data buses and also the first with memory management and wide protection abilities.
[src:dual-in-line-package/80286] It had a data size of 16 bits, and had an address width of 24 bits, which could address up to 16MB of memory with a suitable operating system such as Windows compared to 1MB for the 8086.
[src:dual-in-line-package/80286] The 80286 used approximately 134,000 transistors in its original nMOS (HMOS) incarnation and, just like the contemporary 80186, it can correctly execute most software written for the earlier Intel 8086 and 8088 processors.
[src:dual-in-line-package/80286] The 80286 was employed for the IBM PC/AT, introduced in 1984, and then widely used in most PC/AT compatible computers until the early 1990s.
[src:dual-in-line-package/80286] In 1987, Intel shipped its five-millionth 80286 microprocessor.
[src:dual-in-line-package/80286] Intel's first 80286 chips were specified for a maximum clockrate of 5, 6 or 8 MHz and later releases for 12.5 MHz.
[src:dual-in-line-package/80286] AMD and Harris later produced 16 MHz, 20 MHz and 25 MHz parts.
[src:dual-in-line-package/80286] Intel, Intersil and Fujitsu also designed fully static CMOS versions of Intel's original depletion-load nMOS implementation, largely aimed at battery-powered devices.
[src:dual-in-line-package/80286] Intel's CMOS version of the 80286 was the 80C286.
[src:dual-in-line-package/80286] On average, the 80286 was said to have a speed of about 0.21 instructions per clock on "typical" programs, although it could be significantly faster on optimized code and in tight loops, as many instructions could execute in 2 clock cycles each.
[src:dual-in-line-package/80286] The 6 MHz, 10 MHz, and 12 MHz models were reportedly measured to operate at 0.9 MIPS, 1.5 MIPS, and 2.66 MIPS respectively.
[src:dual-in-line-package/80286] The later E-stepping level of the 80286 was free of the several significant errata that caused problems for programmers and operating-system writers in the earlier B-step and C-step CPUs (common in the AT and AT clones).
[src:dual-in-line-package/80286] This E-2 stepping part may have been available in later 1986.
[src:dual-in-line-package/80286] Intel second sourced this microprocessor to Fujitsu Limited in about 1985.
[src:dual-in-line-package/80286] Intel expected the 286 to be used primarily in industrial automation, transaction processing, and telecommunications, instead of in personal computers.
[src:dual-in-line-package/80286] The CPU was designed for multi-user systems with multitasking applications, including communications (such as automated PBXs) and real-time process control.
[src:dual-in-line-package/80286] It had 134,000 transistors and consisted of four independent units: the address unit, bus unit, instruction unit, and execution unit, organized into a loosely coupled (buffered) pipeline, just as in the 8086.
[src:dual-in-line-package/80286] It was produced in a 68-pin package, including PLCC (plastic leaded chip carrier), LCC (leadless chip carrier) and PGA (pin grid array) packages.
[src:dual-in-line-package/80286] The performance increase of the 80286 over the 8086 (or 8088) could be more than 100% per clock cycle in many programs (i.e., a doubled performance at the same clock speed).
[src:dual-in-line-package/80286] This was a large increase, fully comparable to the speed improvements seven years later when the i486 (1989) or the original Pentium (1993) were introduced.
[src:dual-in-line-package/80286] This was partly due to the non-multiplexed address and data buses, but mainly to the fact that address calculations (such as base+index) were less expensive.
[src:dual-in-line-package/80286] They were performed by a dedicated unit in the 80286, while the older 8086 had to do effective address computation using its general ALU, consuming several extra clock cycles in many cases.
[src:dual-in-line-package/80286] Also, the 80286 was more efficient in the prefetch of instructions, buffering, execution of jumps, and in complex microcoded numerical operations such as MUL/DIV than its predecessor.
[src:dual-in-line-package/80286] The 80286 included, in addition to all of the 8086 instructions, all of the new instructions of the 80186: ENTER, LEAVE, BOUND, INS, OUTS, PUSHA, POPA, PUSH immediate, IMUL immediate, and immediate shifts and rotates.
[src:dual-in-line-package/80286] The 80286 also added new instructions for protected mode: ARPL, CLTS, LAR, LGDT, LIDT, LLDT, LMSW, LSL, LTR, SGDT, SIDT, SLDT, SMSW, STR, VERR, and VERW.
[src:dual-in-line-package/80286] Some of the instructions for protected mode can (or must) be used in real mode to set up and switch to protected mode, and a few (such as SMSW and LMSW) are useful for real mode itself.
[src:dual-in-line-package/80286] The Intel 80286 had a 24-bit address bus and as such had a 16 MB physical address space, compared to the 1 MB address space of prior x86 processors.
[src:dual-in-line-package/80286] It was the first x86 processor to support virtual memory supporting up to 1 GB via segmentation.
[src:dual-in-line-package/80286] However, memory cost and the initial rarity of software using the memory above 1 MB meant that until late in its production, 80286 computers rarely shipped with more than 1 MB of RAM.
[src:dual-in-line-package/80286] Additionally, there was a performance penalty involved in accessing extended memory from real mode as noted below.
[src:dual-in-line-package/80286] The 286 was the first of the x86 CPU family to support *protected virtual-address mode*, commonly called "protected mode".
[src:dual-in-line-package/80286] In addition, it was the first commercially available microprocessor with on-chip memory management unit (MMU) capabilities (systems using the contemporaneous Motorola 68010 and NS320xx could be equipped with an optional MMU controller).
[src:dual-in-line-package/80286] This would allow IBM compatibles to have advanced multitasking OSes for the first time and compete in the Unix-dominated server/workstation market.
[src:dual-in-line-package/80286] Several additional instructions were introduced in the protected mode of 80286, which are helpful for multitasking operating systems.
[src:dual-in-line-package/80286] Another important feature of 80286 is the prevention of unauthorized access.
[src:dual-in-line-package/80286] By design, the 286 could not revert from protected mode to the basic 8086-compatible *real address mode* ("real mode") without a hardware-initiated reset.
[src:dual-in-line-package/80286] (The BIOS is necessarily involved because it obtains control directly whenever the CPU resets.) Though it worked correctly, the method imposed a huge performance penalty.
[src:dual-in-line-package/80286] To support protected mode, new instructions have been added: ARPL, VERR, VERW, LAR, LSL, SMSW, SGDT, SIDT, SLDT, STR, LMSW, LGDT, LIDT, LLDT, LTR, CLTS.
[src:dual-in-line-package/80286] There are also new exceptions (internal interrupts): invalid opcode, coprocessor not available, double fault, coprocessor segment overrun, stack fault, segment overrun/general protection fault, and others only for protected mode.
[src:dual-in-line-package/80286] The protected mode of the 80286 was not routinely utilized in PC applications until many years after its release, in part because of the high cost of adding extended memory to a PC, but also because of the need for software to support the large user base of 8086 PCs.
[src:dual-in-line-package/80286] For example, in 1986 the only program that made use of it was VDISK, a RAM disk driver included with PC DOS 3.0 and 3.1.
[src:dual-in-line-package/80286] PC DOS could use the additional RAM available in protected mode (extended memory) either via a BIOS call (INT 15h, AH=87h), as a RAM disk, or as emulation of expanded memory.
[src:dual-in-line-package/80286] The difficulty lay in the incompatibility of older real-mode programs with protected mode.
[src:dual-in-line-package/80286] They could not natively run in this new mode without significant modification.
[src:dual-in-line-package/80286] In protected mode, memory management and interrupt handling were done differently than in real mode.
[src:dual-in-line-package/80286] In protected mode, registers were still 16-bit, and the programmer was still forced to use a memory map composed of 64 kB segments, just like in real mode.
[src:dual-in-line-package/80286] Intel had not expected the lack of virtual machine support for 8086 software to be a problem, because it thought that new software using all of the 80286's capabilities would quickly appear.
[src:dual-in-line-package/80286] Bill Gates referred to the 80286 as a "brain-damaged" chip, because it cannot use virtual machines to multitask multiple MS-DOS applications with an operating system like Microsoft Windows.
[src:dual-in-line-package/80286] It was arguably responsible for the split between Microsoft and IBM, since IBM insisted that OS/2, originally a joint venture between IBM and Microsoft, would run on a 286 (and in text mode).
[src:dual-in-line-package/80286] In January 1985, Digital Research previewed the Concurrent DOS 286 1.0 operating system developed in cooperation with Intel.
[src:dual-in-line-package/80286] The product would function strictly as an 80286 native-mode (i.e. protected-mode) operating system, allowing users to take full advantage of the protected mode to perform multi-user, multitasking operations while running 8086 emulation.
[src:dual-in-line-package/80286] This worked on the B-1 prototype step of the chip, but Digital Research discovered problems with the emulation on the production level C-1 step in May, which would not allow Concurrent DOS 286 to run 8086 software in protected mode.
[src:dual-in-line-package/80286] The release of Concurrent DOS 286 was delayed until Intel would develop a new version of the chip.
[src:dual-in-line-package/80286] In August, after extensive testing on E-1 step samples of the 80286, Digital Research acknowledged that Intel corrected all documented 286 errata, but said that there were still undocumented chip performance problems with the prerelease version of Concurrent DOS 286 running on the E-1 step.
[src:dual-in-line-package/80286] Intel said that the approach Digital Research wished to take in emulating 8086 software in protected mode differed from the original specifications.
[src:dual-in-line-package/80286] Nevertheless, in the E-2 step, they implemented minor changes in the microcode that would allow Digital Research to run emulation mode much faster.
[src:dual-in-line-package/80286] Named IBM 4680 OS, IBM originally chose DR Concurrent DOS 286 as the basis of their IBM 4680 computer for IBM Plant System products and point-of-sale terminals in 1986.
[src:dual-in-line-package/80286] Digital Research's FlexOS 286 version 1.3, a derivation of Concurrent DOS 286, was developed in 1986, introduced in January 1987, and later adopted by IBM for their IBM 4690 OS, but the same limitations affected it.
[src:dual-in-line-package/80286] Other operating systems that used the protected mode of the 286 were Microsoft Xenix (around 1984), Coherent, and Minix.
[src:dual-in-line-package/80286] These were less hindered by the limitations of the 80286 protected mode because they did not aim to run MS-DOS applications or other real-mode programs.
[src:dual-in-line-package/80286] When designing the 80386 Intel engineers were aware of, and agreed with, the 80286's poor reputation.
[src:dual-in-line-package/80286] They enhanced the 80386's protected mode to address more memory, and also added the separate virtual 8086 mode, a mode within protected mode with much better MS-DOS compatibility.
[src:dual-in-line-package/80286] This is a list of bus interface components that connect to an Intel 80286 microprocessor.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] The **atmosphere of Earth** consists of a layer of mixed gas (commonly referred to as **air**) that is retained by gravity, surrounding the Earth's surface.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] It contains variable quantities of suspended aerosols and particulates that create weather features such as clouds and hazes.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] The atmosphere serves as a protective buffer between the Earth's surface and outer space.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] It shields the surface from most meteoroids and ultraviolet solar radiation, reduces diurnal temperature variation – the temperature extremes between day and night, and keeps it warm through heat retention via the greenhouse effect.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] The atmosphere redistributes heat and moisture among different regions via air currents, and provides the chemical and climate conditions that allow life to exist and evolve on Earth.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] By mole fraction (i.e., by quantity of molecules), dry air contains 78.08% nitrogen, 20.95% oxygen, 0.93% argon, 0.04% carbon dioxide, and small amounts of other trace gases (see Composition below for more detail).
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Air also contains a variable amount of water vapor, on average around 1% at sea level, and 0.4% over the entire atmosphere.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Earth's primordial atmosphere consisted of gases accreted from the solar nebula, but the composition changed significantly over time, affected by many factors such as volcanism, outgassing, impact events, weathering and the evolution of life (particularly the photoautotrophs).
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] In the present day, human activity has contributed to atmospheric changes, such as climate change (mainly through deforestation and fossil-fuel–related global warming), ozone depletion and acid deposition.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] The atmosphere has a mass of about 5.15×1018 kg, three quarters of which is within about 11 km (6.8 mi; 36,000 ft) of the surface.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] The atmosphere becomes thinner with increasing altitude, with no definite boundary between the atmosphere and outer space.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] The Kármán line at 100 km (62 mi) is often used as a conventional definition of the edge of space.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Several layers can be distinguished in the atmosphere based on characteristics such as temperature and composition, namely the troposphere, stratosphere, mesosphere, thermosphere (formally the ionosphere), and exosphere.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Air composition, temperature and atmospheric pressure vary with altitude.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Air suitable for use in photosynthesis by terrestrial plants and respiration of terrestrial animals is found within the troposphere.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] The study of Earth's atmosphere and its processes is called atmospheric science (aerology), and includes multiple subfields, such as climatology and atmospheric physics.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Early pioneers in the field include Léon Teisserenc de Bort and Richard Assmann.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] The study of the historic atmosphere is called paleoclimatology.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] The three major constituents of Earth's atmosphere are nitrogen, oxygen, and argon.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Water vapor accounts for roughly 0.25% of the atmosphere by mass.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] The remaining gases are often referred to as trace gases, among which are other greenhouse gases, principally carbon dioxide, methane, nitrous oxide, and ozone.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Besides argon, other noble gases, neon, helium, krypton, and xenon are also present.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Filtered air includes trace amounts of many other chemical compounds.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Many substances of natural origin may be present in locally and seasonally variable small amounts as aerosols in an unfiltered air sample, including dust of mineral and organic composition, pollen and spores, sea spray, and volcanic ash.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Various industrial pollutants also may be present as gases or aerosols, such as chlorine (elemental or in compounds), fluorine compounds, and elemental mercury vapor.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Sulfur compounds such as hydrogen sulfide and sulfur dioxide (SO2) may be derived from natural sources or from industrial air pollution.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] The average molecular weight of dry air, which can be used to calculate densities or to convert between mole fraction and mass fraction, is about 28.946 or 28.964 g/mol.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] This is decreased when the air is humid.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Up to an altitude of around 100 km (62 mi), atmospheric turbulence mixes the component gases so that their relative concentrations remain the same.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] There exists a transition zone from roughly 80 to 120 km (50 to 75 mi) where this turbulent mixing gradually yields to molecular diffusion.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] The latter process forms the heterosphere where the relative concentration of lighter gases increase with altitude.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] In general, air pressure and density decrease with altitude in the atmosphere.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] However, temperature has a more complicated profile with altitude and may remain relatively constant or even increase with altitude in some regions (see the temperature section).
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Because the general pattern of the temperature/altitude profile, or lapse rate, is constant and measurable by means of instrumented balloon soundings, the temperature behavior provides a useful metric to distinguish atmospheric layers.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] The exosphere is the outermost layer of Earth's atmosphere (though it is so tenuous that some scientists consider it to be part of interplanetary space rather than part of the atmosphere).
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] It extends from the thermopause (also known as the "exobase") at the top of the thermosphere to a poorly defined boundary with the solar wind and interplanetary medium.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] The altitude of the exobase varies from about 500 kilometres (310 mi; 1,600,000 ft) to about 1,000 kilometres (620 mi) in times of higher incoming solar radiation.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] The upper limit varies depending on the definition.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Various authorities consider it to end at about 10,000 kilometres (6,200 mi) or about 190,000 kilometres (120,000 mi)—about halfway to the moon, where the influence of Earth's gravity is about the same as radiation pressure from sunlight.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] The geocorona visible in the far ultraviolet (caused by neutral hydrogen) extends to at least 100,000 kilometres (62,000 mi).
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] This layer is mainly composed of extremely low densities of hydrogen, with limited amounts of helium, carbon dioxide, and nascent oxygen closer to the exobase.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] The atoms and molecules are so far apart that they can travel hundreds of kilometres without colliding with one another.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Thus, the exosphere no longer behaves like a gas, and the particles constantly escape into space.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] These free-moving particles follow ballistic trajectories and may migrate in and out of the magnetosphere or the solar wind.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Every second, the Earth loses about 3 kg of hydrogen, 50 g of helium, and much smaller amounts of other constituents.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] The exosphere is too far above Earth for meteorological phenomena to be possible.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] The exosphere contains many of the artificial satellites that orbit Earth.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] The thermosphere is the second-highest layer of Earth's atmosphere.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] It extends from the mesopause (which separates it from the mesosphere) at an altitude of about 80 km (50 mi) up to the thermopause at an altitude range of 500–1000 km (310–620 mi).
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] The height of the thermopause varies considerably due to changes in solar activity.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] The passage of the dusk and dawn solar terminator creates background density perturbations up to a factor of two through this layer, forming a dominant feature in this region.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Because the thermopause lies at the lower boundary of the exosphere, it is also referred to as the exobase.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Overlapping the thermosphere, from 50 to 600 kilometres (31 to 373 mi) above Earth's surface, is the ionosphere – a region of enhanced plasma density.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] The temperature of the thermosphere gradually increases with height and can rise as high as 1500 °C (2700 °F), though the gas molecules are so far apart that its temperature in the usual sense is not very meaningful.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] This temperature increase is caused by absorption of ionizing UV and X-ray emission from the Sun.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] The air is so rarefied that an individual molecule (of oxygen, for example) travels an average of 1 kilometre (0.62 mi; 3300 ft) between collisions with other molecules.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Although the thermosphere has a high proportion of molecules with high energy, it would not feel hot to a human in direct contact, because its density is too low to conduct a significant amount of energy to or from the skin.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] This layer is completely cloudless and free of water vapor.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] However, non-hydrometeorological phenomena such as the aurora borealis and aurora australis are occasionally seen in the thermosphere at an altitude of around 100 km (62 mi).
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] The colors of the aurora are linked to the properties of the atmosphere at the altitude they occur.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] The most common is the green aurora, which comes from atomic oxygen in the 1S state, and occurs at altitudes from 120 to 400 km (75 to 250 mi).
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] The International Space Station orbits in the thermosphere, between 370 and 460 km (230 and 290 mi).
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] It is this layer where many of the satellites orbiting the Earth are present.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] The mesosphere is the third highest layer of Earth's atmosphere, occupying the region above the stratosphere and below the thermosphere.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] It extends from the stratopause at an altitude of about 50 km (31 mi) to the mesopause at 80–85 km (50–53 mi) above sea level.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Temperatures drop with increasing altitude to the mesopause that marks the top of this middle layer of the atmosphere.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] It is the coldest place on Earth and has an average temperature around −85 °C (−120 °F; 190 K).
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Because the atmosphere absorbs sound waves at a rate that is proportional to the square of the frequency, audible sounds from the ground do not reach the mesosphere.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Infrasonic waves can reach this altitude, but they are difficult to emit at a high power level.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Just below the mesopause, the air is so cold that even the very scarce water vapor at this altitude can condense into polar-mesospheric noctilucent clouds of ice particles.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] These are the highest clouds in the atmosphere and may be visible to the naked eye if sunlight reflects off them about an hour or two after sunset or similarly before sunrise.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] They are most readily visible when the Sun is around 4 to 16 degrees below the horizon.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Lightning-induced discharges known as transient luminous events (TLEs) occasionally form in the mesosphere above tropospheric thunderclouds.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] The mesosphere is also the layer where most meteors and satellites burn up upon atmospheric entrance.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] It is too high above Earth to be accessible to jet-powered aircraft and balloons, and too low to permit orbital spacecraft.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] The mesosphere is mainly accessed by sounding rockets and rocket-powered aircraft.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] The stratosphere is the second-lowest layer of Earth's atmosphere.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] It lies above the troposphere and is separated from it by the tropopause.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] This layer extends from the top of the troposphere at roughly 12 km (7.5 mi) above Earth's surface to the stratopause at an altitude of about 50 to 55 km (31 to 34 mi).
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] 99% of the total mass of the atmosphere lies below 30 km (19 mi), and the atmospheric pressure at the top of the stratosphere is roughly 1/1000 the pressure at sea level.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] It contains the ozone layer, which is the part of Earth's atmosphere that contains relatively high concentrations of that gas.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] The stratosphere defines a layer in which temperatures rise with increasing altitude.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] This rise in temperature is caused by the absorption of ultraviolet radiation (UV) from the Sun by the ozone layer, which restricts turbulence and mixing.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Although the temperature may be −80 °C (−110 °F; 190 K) at the tropopause, the top of the stratosphere is much warmer, and may be just below 0 °C.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] This layer is unique to the Earth; neither Mars nor Venus have a stratosphere because of low abundances of oxygen in their atmospheres.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] The stratospheric temperature profile creates very stable atmospheric conditions, so the stratosphere lacks the weather-producing air turbulence that is so prevalent in the troposphere.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Consequently, the stratosphere is almost completely free of clouds and other forms of weather.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] However, polar stratospheric or nacreous clouds are occasionally seen in the lower part of this layer of the atmosphere where the air is coldest.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] The stratosphere is the highest layer that can be accessed by jet-powered aircraft.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] The troposphere is the lowest layer of Earth's atmosphere.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] It extends from Earth's surface to an average height of about 12 km (7.5 mi), although this altitude varies from about 9 km (5.6 mi) at the geographic poles to 17 km (11 mi) at the Equator, with some variation due to weather.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] The troposphere is bounded above by the tropopause, a boundary marked in most places by a temperature inversion (i.e. a layer of relatively warm air above a colder one), and in others by a zone that is isothermal with height.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Although variations do occur, the temperature usually declines with increasing altitude in the troposphere because the troposphere is mostly heated through energy transfer from the surface.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Thus, the lowest part of the troposphere (i.e.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Earth's surface) is typically the warmest section of the troposphere.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] This promotes vertical mixing (hence, the origin of its name in the Greek word τρόπος, *tropos*, meaning "turn").
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] The troposphere contains roughly 80% of the mass of Earth's atmosphere.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] The troposphere is denser than all its overlying layers because a larger atmospheric weight sits on top of the troposphere and causes it to be more severely compressed.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Fifty percent of the total mass of the atmosphere is located in the lower 5.5 km (3.4 mi) of the troposphere.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Nearly all atmospheric water vapor or moisture is found in the troposphere, so it is the layer where most of Earth's weather takes place.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] The ability of the atmosphere to retain water decreases as the temperature declines, so 90% of the water vapor is held in the lower part of the troposphere.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] It has basically all the weather-associated cloud genus types generated by active wind circulation, although very tall cumulonimbus thunder clouds can penetrate the tropopause from below and rise into the lower part of the stratosphere.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Most conventional aviation activity takes place in the troposphere, and it is the only layer accessible by propeller-driven aircraft.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Contrails are formed from jet engine water emission at altitudes where the atmospheric temperature is about −53 °C (−63 °F); typically around 7.7 km (4.8 mi) for modern engines.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Above this altitude lies the heterosphere, which includes the exosphere and most of the thermosphere.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Here, the chemical composition varies with altitude.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] is large compared with the size of motions that cause mixing.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] with the heavier ones, such as oxygen and nitrogen, present only near the bottom of the heterosphere.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] The upper part of the heterosphere is composed almost completely of hydrogen, the lightest element.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] The average temperature of the atmosphere at Earth's surface is 14 °C (57 °F; 287 K) or 15 °C (59 °F; 288 K), depending on the reference.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] The average atmospheric pressure at sea level is defined by the International Standard Atmosphere as 101325 pascals (760.00 Torr; 14.6959 psi; 760.00 mmHg).
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] This is sometimes referred to as a unit of standard atmospheres (atm).
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Total atmospheric mass is 5.1480×1018 kg (1.13494×1019 lb), about 2.5% less than would be inferred from the average sea-level pressure and Earth's area of 51007.2 megahectares, this portion being displaced by Earth's mountainous terrain.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Atmospheric pressure is the total weight of the air above unit area at the point where the pressure is measured.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Thus air pressure varies with location and weather.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Air pressure decreases exponentially with altitude at a rate that depends on the air temperature.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] The rate of decrease is determined by a temperature-dependent parameter called the scale height: for each increase in altitude by this height, the pressure decreases by a factor of *e* (the base of natural logarithms, approximately 2.718).
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] For Earth, this value is typically 5.5 to 6 km for altitudes up to around 80 km (50 mi).
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] However, the atmosphere is more accurately modeled with a customized equation for each layer that takes gradients of temperature, molecular composition, solar radiation and gravity into account.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] At heights over 100 km, the atmosphere is not well mixed, so each chemical species has its own scale height.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] At altitudes of 200 to 300 km, the combined scale height is 20 to 30 km.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Even above the Kármán line, significant atmospheric effects such as auroras still occur.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Meteors begin to glow in this region, though the larger ones may not burn up until they penetrate more deeply.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] The various layers of Earth's ionosphere, important to HF radio propagation, begin below 100 km and extend beyond 500 km.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] By comparison, the International Space Station typically orbit at 370–460 km, within the F-layer of the ionosphere, where they encounter enough atmospheric drag to require reboosts every few months, otherwise orbital decay will occur, resulting in a return to Earth.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Depending on solar activity, satellites can experience noticeable atmospheric drag at altitudes as high as 600–800 km.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Starting at sea level, the temperature decreases with altitude until reaching the stratosphere at around 11 km.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Above, the temperature stabilizes over a large vertical distance.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Starting above about 20 km, the temperature increases with height, due to heating within the ozone layer caused by the capture of significant ultraviolet radiation from the Sun by the molecular oxygen and ozone gas in this region.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] A second region of increasing temperature with altitude occurs at very high altitudes, in the aptly-named thermosphere above 90 km.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] During the night, the ground radiates more energy than it gains from the atmosphere.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] As energy is conducted from the nearby atmosphere to the cooler ground, it creates a temperature inversion where the local temperature increases with altitude up to around 1,000 m.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] For example, at sea level the speed of sound is 340 m/s.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] At the average temperature of the stratosphere, −60 °C, the speed of sound decreases to 290 m/s.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Density is not measured directly but is calculated from measurements of temperature, pressure and humidity using the equation of state for air (a form of the ideal gas law).
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Atmospheric density decreases as the altitude increases.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] This variation can be approximately modeled using the barometric formula.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] More sophisticated models are used to predict the orbital decay of satellites.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] The average mass of the atmosphere is about 5 quadrillion (5×1015) tonnes or 1/1,200,000 the mass of Earth.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] According to the American National Center for Atmospheric Research, "The total mean mass of the atmosphere is 5.1480×1018 kg with an annual range due to water vapor of 1.2 or 1.5×1015 kg, depending on whether surface pressure or water vapor data are used; somewhat smaller than the previous estimate.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Solar radiation (or sunlight) is the energy Earth receives from the Sun.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Earth also emits radiation back into space, but at longer wavelengths that humans cannot see.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] As energy propagates through the atmosphere, it is impacted by the process of radiative transfer.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] That is, some of the incoming and emitted radiation is subject to absorption, emission, and scattering by the atmosphere.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Another portion of the incident energy is reflected, with the two most important atmospheric reflectors being dust and clouds.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Depending on the properties of the aerosol, clouds can reflect up to 70% of the incident radiation.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Globally, clouds reflect 20% of the incoming energy, contributing two thirds of the planet's total albedo.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] In May 2017, glints of light, seen as twinkling from an orbiting satellite a million miles away, were found to be reflected light from ice crystals in the troposphere.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] When light passes through Earth's atmosphere, photons interact with it through *scattering*.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] If the light does not interact with the atmosphere, it is called *direct radiation* and is what you see if you were to look directly at the Sun.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] *Indirect radiation* is light that has been scattered in the atmosphere.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] For example, on an overcast day when you cannot see your shadow, there is no direct radiation reaching you, it has all been scattered.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] As another example, due to a phenomenon called Rayleigh scattering, shorter (blue) wavelengths scatter more easily than longer (red) wavelengths.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] This is why the sky looks blue; you are seeing scattered blue light.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Because the Sun is close to the horizon, the Sun's rays pass through more atmosphere than normal before reaching your eye.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Much of the blue light has been scattered out, leaving the red light in a sunset.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Different molecules absorb different wavelengths of radiation.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] For example, O2 and O3 absorb almost all radiation with wavelengths shorter than 300 nanometres.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Water (H2O) absorbs at many wavelengths above 700 nm.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] When a molecule absorbs a photon, it increases the energy of the molecule.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] This heats the atmosphere, but the atmosphere also cools by emitting radiation, as discussed below.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] In astronomical spectroscopy, the absorption of specific frequencies by the atmosphere is referred to as telluric contamination.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] The combined absorption spectra of the gases in the atmosphere leave "windows" of low opacity, allowing the transmission of only certain bands of light.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] The optical window runs from around 300 nm (ultraviolet-C) up into the range humans can see, the visible spectrum (commonly called light), at roughly 400–700 nm and continues to the infrared to around 1100 nm.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] There are also infrared and radio windows that transmit some infrared and radio waves at longer wavelengths.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] For example, the radio window runs from about one centimetre to about eleven-metre waves.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Because of its temperature, the atmosphere emits infrared radiation.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] For example, on clear nights Earth's surface cools down faster than on cloudy nights.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] This is because clouds (H2O) are strong absorbers and emitters of infrared radiation.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] This is also why it becomes colder at night at higher elevations.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] The greenhouse effect is directly related to this absorption and emission effect.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Some gases in the atmosphere absorb and emit infrared radiation, but do not interact in this manner with sunlight in the visible spectrum.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Common examples of these are CO2 and H2O.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Without greenhouse gases in the atmosphere, the average temperature of Earth's surface would be a frozen −18 °C (0 °F), rather than the present comfortable average of 15 °C (59 °F).
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] The refractive index of air is close to, but just greater than, 1.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Systematic variations in the refractive index can lead to the bending of light rays over long optical paths.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] One example is that, under some circumstances, observers on board ships can see other vessels just over the horizon because light is refracted in the same direction as the curvature of Earth's surface.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] The refractive index of air depends on temperature, giving rise to refraction effects when the temperature gradient is large.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] An example of such effects is the mirage.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] The flow of air around the planet is divided into three main convection cells by latitude.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Around the equator, the Hadley cell is driven by the rising flow of air along the equator.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] In the upper atmosphere, this air flows toward the poles.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] At mid latitudes, this circulation is reversed, with ground air flowing toward the poles with the Ferrel cell.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Finally, in the high latitudes is the Polar cell, where air again rises and flows toward the poles.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] The interface between these cells is responsible for jet streams.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] These are narrow, fast moving bands that flow from west to east and typically form at an elevation of around 9,100 m (30,000 ft).
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Jet streams can shift around depending on conditions.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] They are strongest in winter, when the boundaries between hot and cold air are the most pronounced.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] In the middle latitudes, it is instabilities in the jet streams that are responsible for moving weather systems.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] As with the oceans, the Earth's atmosphere is subject to waves and tidal forces.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] These are triggered by non-uniform heating by the Sun, and by the daily solar cycle, respectively.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Wave-like behavior can occur on a variety of scales, from smaller gravity waves that transfer momentum into the higher atmospheric layers, to much larger planetary waves, or Rossby waves.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Atmospheric tides are periodic oscillations of the troposphere and stratosphere that transport energy to the upper atmosphere.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] The first atmosphere, during the Early Earth's Hadean eon, consisted of gases in the solar nebula, primarily hydrogen, and probably simple hydrides such as those now found in the gas giants (Jupiter and Saturn), notably water vapor, methane and ammonia.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] During this earliest era, the Moon-forming collision and numerous impacts with large meteorites heated the atmosphere, driving off the most volatile gases.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] The collision with Theia, in particular, melted and ejected large portions of Earth's mantle and crust and outgassed significant amounts of steam which eventually cooled and condensed to contribute to ocean water at the end of the Hadean.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] The increasing solidification of Earth's crust at the end of the Hadean closed off most of the advective heat transfer to the surface, causing the atmosphere to cool, which condensed most of the water vapor out of the air precipitating into a superocean.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Further outgassing from volcanism, supplemented by gases introduced by huge asteroids during the Late Heavy Bombardment, created the subsequent Archean atmosphere, which consisted largely of nitrogen plus carbon dioxide, methane and inert gases.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] A major part of carbon dioxide emissions dissolved in water and reacted with metals such as calcium and magnesium during weathering of crustal rocks to form carbonates that were deposited as sediments.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Water-related sediments have been found that date from as early as 3.8 billion years ago.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] About 3.4 billion years ago, nitrogen formed the major component of the then-stable "second atmosphere".
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] The influence of the evolution of life has to be taken into account rather soon in the history of the atmosphere because hints of earliest life forms appeared as early as 3.5 billion years ago.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] How Earth at that time maintained a climate warm enough for liquid water and life, if the early Sun put out 30% lower solar radiance than today, is a puzzle known as the "faint young Sun paradox".
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] The geological record however shows a continuous relatively warm surface during the complete early temperature record of Earth – with the exception of one cold glacial phase about 2.4 billion years ago.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] In the late Neoarchean, an oxygen-containing atmosphere began to develop, apparently due to a billion years of cyanobacterial photosynthesis (known as the Great Oxygenation Event), which have been found as stromatolite fossils from 2.7 billion years ago.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] The early basic carbon isotopy (isotope ratio proportions) strongly suggests conditions similar to the current, and that the fundamental features of the carbon cycle became established as early as 4 billion years ago.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Ancient sediments in the Gabon dating from between about 2.15 and 2.08 billion years ago provide a record of Earth's dynamic oxygenation evolution.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] These fluctuations in oxygenation were likely driven by the Lomagundi-Jatuli Carbon Isotope Excursion.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] The constant re-arrangement of continents by plate tectonics influences the long-term evolution of the atmosphere by transferring carbon dioxide to and from large continental carbonate stores.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Before this time, any oxygen produced by cyanobacterial photosynthesis would be readily removed by the oxidation of reducing substances on the Earth's surface, notably ferrous iron, sulfur and atmospheric methane.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Free oxygen molecules did not start to accumulate in the atmosphere until the rate of production of oxygen began to exceed the availability of reductant materials that removed oxygen.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] This point signifies a shift from a reducing atmosphere to an oxidizing atmosphere.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] O2 showed major variations during the Proterozoic, including a billion-year period of euxinia, until reaching a steady state of more than 15% by the end of the Precambrian.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] The amount of oxygen in the atmosphere has fluctuated over the last 600 million years, reaching a peak of about 35% around 280 million years ago during the Carboniferous period, significantly higher than today's 21%.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Two main processes govern changes in the atmosphere: the evolution of plants and their increasing role in carbon fixation, and the consumption of oxygen by rapidly diversifying animal faunae and also by plants for photorespiration and their own metabolic needs at night.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Breakdown of pyrite and volcanic eruptions release sulfur into the atmosphere, which reacts and hence reduces oxygen in the atmosphere.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] However, volcanic eruptions also release carbon dioxide, which can fuel oxygenic photosynthesis by terrestrial and aquatic plants.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] The cause of the variation of the amount of oxygen in the atmosphere is not precisely understood.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Periods with more oxygen in the atmosphere were often associated with more rapid development of animals.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Since 1750, human activity, especially after the Industrial Revolution, has increased the concentrations of various greenhouse gases, most importantly carbon dioxide, methane and nitrous oxide.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] Greenhouse gas emissions, coupled with deforestation and destruction of wetlands via logging and land developments, have caused an observed rise in global temperatures, with the global average surface temperatures being 1.1 °C higher in the 2011–2020 decade than they were in 1850.
[src:dual-in-line-package/air] It has raised concerns of man-made climate change, which can have significant environmental impacts such as sea level rise, ocean acidification, glacial retreat (which threatens water security), increasing extreme weather events and wildfires, ecological collapse and mass dying of wildlife.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] Arduino board designs use a variety of microprocessors and controllers.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] The boards are equipped with sets of digital and analog input/output (I/O) pins that may be interfaced to various expansion boards ('shields') or breadboards (for prototyping) and other circuits.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] The boards feature serial communications interfaces, including Universal Serial Bus (USB) on some models, which are also used for loading programs.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] The microcontrollers can be programmed using the C and C++ programming languages (Embedded C), using a standard API which is also known as the **Arduino Programming Language**, inspired by the Processing language and used with a modified version of the Processing IDE.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] In addition to using traditional compiler toolchains, the Arduino project provides an integrated development environment (IDE) and a command line tool developed in Go.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] The Arduino project began in 2005 as a tool for students at the Interaction Design Institute Ivrea, Italy, aiming to provide a low-cost and easy way for novices and professionals to create devices that interact with their environment using sensors and actuators.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] Common examples of such devices intended for makers include simple robots, thermostats, and motion detectors.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] The name *Arduino* comes from the Bar di Re Arduino, where some of the project's founders used to meet.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] This bar is in Ivrea, Italy and was named after Arduin.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] The Arduino project was started at the Interaction Design Institute Ivrea (IDII) in Ivrea, Italy.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] At that time, the students used a BASIC Stamp microcontroller at a cost of $50.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] In 2004, Hernando Barragán created the development platform *Wiring* as a Master's thesis project at IDII, under the supervision of Massimo Banzi and Casey Reas.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] Casey Reas is known for co-creating, with Ben Fry, the Processing development platform.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] The project goal was to create simple, low cost tools for creating digital projects by non-engineers.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] The Wiring platform consisted of a printed circuit board (PCB) with an ATmega128 microcontroller, an IDE based on Processing and library functions to easily program the microcontroller.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] In 2005, Massimo Banzi, with David Mellis, another IDII student, and David Cuartielles, extended Wiring by adding support for the cheaper ATmega8 microcontroller.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] The new project, forked from Wiring, was called *Arduino*.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] The initial Arduino core team consisted of Massimo Banzi, David Cuartielles, Tom Igoe, Gianluca Martino, and David Mellis.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] Following the completion of the platform, lighter and less expensive versions were distributed in the open-source community.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] It was estimated in mid-2011 that over 300,000 official Arduinos had been commercially produced, and in 2013 that 700,000 official boards were in users' hands.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] In early 2008, the five co-founders of the Arduino project created a company, Arduino LLC, to hold the trademarks associated with Arduino.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] The manufacture and sale of the boards were to be done by external companies, and Arduino LLC would get a royalty from them.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] The founding bylaws of Arduino LLC specified that each of the five founders transfer ownership of the Arduino brand to the newly formed company.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] At the end of 2008, Gianluca Martino's company, Smart Projects, registered the Arduino trademark in Italy and kept this a secret from the other co-founders for about two years.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] This was revealed when the Arduino company tried to register the trademark in other areas of the world (they originally registered only in the US), and discovered that it was already registered in Italy.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] Negotiations with Martino and his firm to bring the trademark under the control of the original Arduino company failed.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] In 2014, Smart Projects began refusing to pay royalties.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] They then appointed a new CEO, Federico Musto, who renamed the company *Arduino SRL* and created the website *arduino.org*, copying the graphics and layout of the original *arduino.cc*.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] This resulted in a rift in the Arduino development team.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] In January 2015, Arduino LLC filed a lawsuit against Arduino SRL.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] In May 2015, Arduino LLC created the worldwide trademark **Genuino**, used as brand name outside the United States.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] At the World Maker Faire in New York on 1 October 2016, Arduino LLC co-founder and CEO Massimo Banzi and Arduino SRL CEO Federico Musto announced the merger of the two companies, forming Arduino AG.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] Around that same time, Massimo Banzi announced that in addition to the company a new Arduino Foundation would be launched as "a new beginning for Arduino", but this decision was withdrawn later.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] In April 2017, Wired reported that Musto had "fabricated his academic record...
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] On his company's website, personal LinkedIn accounts, and even on Italian business documents, Musto was, until recently, listed as holding a Ph.D. from the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] In some cases, his biography also claimed an MBA from New York University." Wired reported that neither university had any record of Musto's attendance, and Musto later admitted in an interview with Wired that he had never earned those degrees.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] The controversy surrounding Musto continued when, in July 2017, he reportedly pulled many open source licenses, schematics, and code from the Arduino website, prompting scrutiny and outcry.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] By 2017 Arduino 'AG' owned many Arduino trademarks.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] In July 2017 BCMI, founded by Massimo Banzi, David Cuartielles, David Mellis and Tom Igoe, acquired Arduino AG and all the Arduino trademarks.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] Fabio Violante is the new CEO replacing Federico Musto, who no longer works for Arduino AG.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] In October 2017, Arduino announced its partnership with Arm Holdings (ARM).
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] The announcement said, in part, "ARM recognized independence as a core value of Arduino ... without any lock-in with the ARM architecture".
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] Arduino intends to continue to work with all technology vendors and architectures.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] Under Violante's guidance, the company started growing again and releasing new designs.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] The Genuino trademark was dismissed and all products were branded again with the Arduino name.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] In August 2018, Arduino announced its new open source command line tool (arduino-cli), which can be used as a replacement of the IDE to program the boards from a shell.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] In February 2019, Arduino announced its IoT Cloud service as an extension of the Create online environment.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] As of February 2020, the Arduino community included about 30 million active users based on the IDE downloads.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] In October 2025 it was announced that Arduino has been acquired, for an as yet undisclosed amount, by the American semiconductor multinational Qualcomm.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] The hardware reference designs are distributed under a Creative Commons Attribution Share-Alike 2.5 license and are available on the Arduino website.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] Layout and production files for some versions of the hardware are also available.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] Although the hardware and software designs are freely available under copyleft licenses, the developers have requested the name *Arduino* to be exclusive to the official product and not be used for derived works without permission.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] The official policy document on the use of the Arduino name emphasizes that the project is open to incorporating work by others into the official product.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] Several Arduino-compatible products commercially released have avoided the project name by using various names ending in *-duino*.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] Most Arduino boards consist of an Atmel 8-bit AVR microcontroller (ATmega8, ATmega168, ATmega328, ATmega1280, or ATmega2560) with varying amounts of flash memory, pins, and features.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] The 32-bit Arduino Due, based on the Atmel SAM3X8E was introduced in 2012.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] The boards use single or double-row pins or female headers that facilitate connections for programming and incorporation into other circuits.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] These may connect with add-on modules termed *shields*.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] Multiple and possibly stacked shields may be individually addressable via an I²C serial bus.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] Most boards include a 5 V linear regulator and a 16 MHz crystal oscillator or ceramic resonator.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] Some designs, such as the LilyPad, run at 8 MHz and dispense with the onboard voltage regulator due to specific form factor restrictions.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] Arduino microcontrollers are pre-programmed with a bootloader that simplifies the uploading of programs to the on-chip flash memory.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] The default bootloader of the Arduino Uno is the Optiboot bootloader.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] Boards are loaded with program code via a serial connection to another computer.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] Some serial Arduino boards contain a level shifter circuit to convert between RS-232 logic levels and transistor–transistor logic (TTL serial) level signals.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] Current Arduino boards are programmed via Universal Serial Bus (USB), implemented using USB-to-serial adapter chips such as the FTDI FT232.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] Some boards, such as later-model Uno boards, substitute the FTDI chip with a separate AVR chip containing USB-to-serial firmware, which is reprogrammable via its own ICSP header.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] Other variants, such as the Arduino Mini and the unofficial Boarduino, use a detachable USB-to-serial adapter board or cable, Bluetooth or other methods.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] When used with traditional microcontroller tools, instead of the Arduino IDE, standard AVR in-system programming (ISP) programming is used.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] The Arduino board exposes most of the microcontroller's I/O pins for use by other circuits.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] The *Diecimila*, *Duemilanove*, and current *Uno* provide 14 digital I/O pins, six of which can produce pulse-width modulated(PWM) signals, and six analog inputs, which can also be used as six digital I/O pins.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] These pins are on the top of the board, via female 0.1-inch (2.54 mm) headers.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] Several plug-in application shields are also commercially available.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] The Arduino Nano and Arduino-compatible Bare Bones Board and Boarduino boards may provide male header pins on the underside of the board that can plug into solderless breadboards.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] Many Arduino-compatible and Arduino-derived boards exist.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] Some are functionally equivalent to an Arduino and can be used interchangeably.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] Many enhance the basic Arduino by adding output drivers, often for use in school-level education, to simplify making buggies and small robots.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] Others are electrically equivalent, but change the form factor, sometimes retaining compatibility with shields, sometimes not.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] Some variants use different processors, of varying compatibility.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] In addition to hardware variations, open source libraries have been developed to support Arduino hardware in EDA tools.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] One such project provides KiCad schematic symbols and PCB footprints for Arduino modules, expansion boards, and connectors, making it easier for engineers to integrate Arduino into their designs.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] The original Arduino hardware was manufactured by the Italian company Smart Projects.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] Some Arduino-branded boards have been designed by the American companies SparkFun Electronics and Adafruit Industries.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] As of 2016, 17 versions of the Arduino hardware have been commercially produced.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] Arduino shields are add-on boards that stack onto Arduino mainboards to extend their functionality for specific tasks.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] Common uses include controlling DC motors for a robot, for 3D printer, adding a LCD display, enabling Ethernet connectivity, providing GPS/ GNSS navigation and converting pin headers into Grove connectors.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] Shields are typically designed and manufactured by third-party hardware companies, including SparkFun Electronics, Adafruit Industries, Seeed Studio, and Cytron Technologies, among others.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] Several shields can also be made do it yourself (DIY).
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] A program for Arduino hardware may be written in any programming language with compilers that produce binary machine code for the target processor.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] Atmel provides a development environment for their 8-bit AVR and 32-bit ARM Cortex-M based microcontrollers: AVR Studio (older) and Atmel Studio (newer).
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] The Arduino integrated development environment (IDE) is a cross-platform application (for Microsoft Windows, macOS, and Linux) that is based on *Processing IDE* which is written in Java.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] It uses the *Wiring* API as programming style and HAL.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] It includes a code editor with features such as text cutting and pasting, searching and replacing text, automatic indenting, brace matching, and syntax highlighting, and provides simple *one-click* mechanisms to compile and upload programs to an Arduino board.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] It also contains a message area, a text console, a toolbar with buttons for common functions and a hierarchy of operation menus.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] The source code for the IDE is released under the GNU General Public License, version 2.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] The Arduino IDE supports the languages C and C++ using special rules of code structuring.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] The Arduino IDE supplies a software library from the Wiring project, which provides many common input and output procedures.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] User-written code only requires two basic functions, for starting the sketch and the main program loop, that are compiled and linked with a program stub *main()* into an executable cyclic executive program with the GNU toolchain, also included with the IDE distribution.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] The Arduino IDE employs the program *avrdude* to convert the executable code into a text file in hexadecimal encoding that is loaded into the Arduino board by a loader program in the board's firmware.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] An initial alpha preview of a new Arduino IDE was released on October 18, 2019, as Arduino Pro IDE.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] The beta preview was released on March 1, 2021, renamed IDE 2.0.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] On September 14, 2022, the Arduino IDE 2.0 was officially released as stable.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] The system still uses Arduino CLI (Command Line Interface), but improvements include a more professional development environment and autocompletion support.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] The application frontend is based on the Eclipse Theia Open Source IDE.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] One important feature Arduino IDE 2.0 provides is the debugging feature.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] It allows users to single-step, insert breakpoints or view memory.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] Debugging requires a target chip with debug port and a debug probe.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] The official Arduino Zero board can be debugged out of the box.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] Other official Arduino SAMD21 boards require a separate SEGGER J-Link or Atmel-ICE.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] For a 3rd party board, debugging in Arduino IDE 2.0 is also possible as long as such board supports GDB, OPENOCD and has a debug probe.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] Community has contributed debugging for ATMega328P based Arduino or CH32 RISC-V boards, etc.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] A *sketch* is a program written with the Arduino IDE.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] Sketches are saved on the development computer as text files with the file extension **.ino**.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] Arduino Software (IDE) pre-1.0 saved sketches with the extension **.pde**.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] Most Arduino boards contain a light-emitting diode (LED) and a current-limiting resistor connected between pin 13 and ground, which is a convenient feature for many tests and program functions.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] A typical program used by beginners, akin to Hello, World!, is "blink", which repeatedly blinks the on-board LED integrated into the Arduino board.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] This program uses the functions `pinMode()`, `digitalWrite()`, and `delay()`, which are provided by the internal libraries included in the IDE environment.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] This program is usually loaded into a new Arduino board by the manufacturer.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] The open-source nature of the Arduino project has facilitated the publication of many free software libraries that other developers use to augment their projects.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] There is a Xinu OS port for the ATmega328P (Arduino Uno and others with the same chip), which includes most of the basic features.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] The source code of this version is freely available.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] There is also a threading tool, named Protothreads.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] Protothreads are described as "extremely lightweight stackless threads designed for severely memory constrained systems, such as small embedded systems or wireless sensor network nodes.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] There is a port of FreeRTOS for the Arduino.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] This is available from the Arduino Library Manager.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] It is compatible with a number of boards, including the Uno.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] The Arduino project received an honorary mention in the Digital Communities category at the 2006 Prix Ars Electronica.
[src:dual-in-line-package/arduino] The Arduino Engineering Kit won the Bett Award for "Higher Education or Further Education Digital Services" in 2020.
[src:dual-in-line-package/atmega328] The **ATmega328** is a single-chip microcontroller created by Atmel in the megaAVR family (later Microchip Technology acquired Atmel in 2016).
[src:dual-in-line-package/atmega328] It has a modified Harvard architecture 8-bit RISC processor core.
[src:dual-in-line-package/atmega328] The device operates between 1.8 and 5.5 volts.
[src:dual-in-line-package/atmega328] The device achieves throughput approaching 1 MIPS/MHz.
[src:dual-in-line-package/atmega328] A common alternative to the ATmega328 is the "picoPower" ATmega328P.
[src:dual-in-line-package/atmega328] A comprehensive list of all other members of the megaAVR series can be found on the Atmel website.
[src:dual-in-line-package/atmega328] ATmega328 is commonly used in many projects and autonomous systems where a simple, low-powered, low-cost micro-controller is needed.
[src:dual-in-line-package/atmega328] Perhaps the most common use of this chip is on the popular Arduino development platform, namely the Arduino Uno, Arduino Pro Mini and Arduino Nano models.
[src:dual-in-line-package/atmega328] Reliability qualification shows that the projected data retention failure rate is much less than 1 PPM over 20 years at 85 °C or 100 years at 25 °C.
[src:dual-in-line-package/atmega328] Programming mode is entered when PAGEL (PD7), XA1 (PD6), XA0 (PD5), BS1 (PD4) is set to zero.
[src:dual-in-line-package/atmega328] Serial data to the MCU is clocked on the rising edge and data from the MCU is clocked on the falling edge.
[src:dual-in-line-package/atmega328] Power is applied to VCC while RESET and SCK are set to zero.
[src:dual-in-line-package/atmega328] Wait for at least 20 ms and then the programming enable serial instruction 0xAC, 0x53, 0x00, 0x00 is sent to the MOSI pin.
[src:dual-in-line-package/atmega328] The second byte (0x53) will be echoed back by the MCU.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] In computing, **BIOS** or the **Basic Input/Output System** is a type of firmware used to provide runtime services for operating systems and programs and to perform hardware initialization during the booting process (power-on startup).
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] On a computer using BIOS firmware, the firmware comes pre-installed on the computer's motherboard.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] The name originates from the **B**asic **I**nput/**O**utput **S**ystem used in the CP/M operating system in 1975.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] The BIOS firmware was originally proprietary to the IBM PC; it was reverse engineered by some companies, such as Compaq, Phoenix Technologies, AMI and others, looking to create compatible systems.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] The interface of that original system serves as a *de facto* standard.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] The BIOS in older PCs initializes and tests the system hardware components (power-on self-test or POST for short), and loads a boot loader from a mass storage device which then initializes a kernel.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] In the era of DOS, the BIOS provided BIOS interrupt calls for the keyboard, display, storage, and other input/output (I/O) devices that standardized an interface to application programs and the operating system.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] More recent operating systems do not use the BIOS interrupt calls after startup.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Most BIOS implementations are specifically designed to work with a particular computer or motherboard model, by interfacing with various devices especially system chipset.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Originally, BIOS firmware was stored in a ROM chip on the PC motherboard.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] In later computer systems, the BIOS contents are stored on flash memory so it can be rewritten without removing the chip from the motherboard.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] This allows easy, end-user updates to the BIOS firmware so new features can be added or bugs can be fixed, but it also creates a possibility for the computer to become infected with BIOS rootkits.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Furthermore, a BIOS upgrade that fails could brick the motherboard.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Unified Extensible Firmware Interface (UEFI) is a successor to the legacy PC BIOS, aiming to address its technical limitations.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] UEFI firmware may include legacy BIOS compatibility to maintain compatibility with operating systems and option cards that do not support UEFI native operation.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Intel phased out providing support for booting from the BIOS interface from 2020 to 2024 depending on the platform.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] The last version of Microsoft Windows to officially support running on PCs which use legacy BIOS firmware is Windows 10 as Windows 11 requires a UEFI-compliant system (except for IoT Enterprise editions of Windows 11 since version 24H2).
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] The term BIOS (Basic Input/Output System) was created by Gary Kildall and first appeared in the CP/M operating system in 1975, describing the machine-specific part of CP/M loaded during boot time that interfaces directly with the hardware.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Versions of MS-DOS, PC DOS or DR-DOS contain a file called variously "IO.SYS", "IBMBIO.COM", "IBMBIO.SYS", or "DRBIOS.SYS"; this file is known as the "DOS BIOS" (also known as the "DOS I/O System") and contains the lower-level hardware-specific part of the operating system.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Together with the underlying hardware-specific but operating system-independent "System BIOS", which resides in ROM, it represents the analogue to the "CP/M BIOS".
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] The BIOS originally proprietary to the IBM PC has been reverse engineered by some companies, such as Compaq, Phoenix Technologies, AMI and others, looking to create compatible systems.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] With the introduction of PS/2 machines, IBM divided the System BIOS into real- and protected-mode portions.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] The BIOS of the original IBM PC and XT had no interactive user interface.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Error codes or messages were displayed on the screen, or coded series of sounds were generated to signal errors when the power-on self-test (POST) had not proceeded to the point of successfully initializing a video display adapter.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Options on the IBM PC and XT were set by switches and jumpers on the main board and on expansion cards.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Starting around the mid-1990s, it became typical for the BIOS ROM to include a *"BIOS configuration utility"* (BCU) or "BIOS setup utility", accessed at system power-up by a particular key sequence.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] This program allowed the user to set system configuration options, of the type formerly set using DIP switches, through an interactive menu system controlled through the keyboard.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] In the interim period, IBM-compatible PCs‍—‌including the IBM AT‍—‌held configuration settings in battery-backed RAM and used a bootable configuration program on floppy disk, not in the ROM, to set the configuration options contained in this memory.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] The floppy disk was supplied with the computer, and if it was lost the system settings could not be changed.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] The same applied in general to computers with an EISA bus, for which the configuration program was called an EISA Configuration Utility (ECU).
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] A modern Wintel-compatible computer provides a setup routine essentially unchanged in nature from the ROM-resident BIOS setup utilities of the late 1990s; the user can configure hardware options using the keyboard and video display.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] The modern Wintel machine may store the BIOS configuration settings in flash ROM, perhaps the same flash ROM that holds the BIOS itself.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Peripheral cards such as hard disk drive host bus adapters and video cards have their own firmware, and BIOS extension option ROM code may be a part of the expansion card firmware; that code provides additional capabilities in the BIOS.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Code in option ROMs runs before the BIOS boots the operating system from mass storage.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] These ROMs typically test and initialize hardware, add new BIOS services, or replace existing BIOS services with their own services.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] For example, a SCSI controller usually has a BIOS extension ROM that adds support for hard drives connected through that controller.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] An extension ROM could in principle contain operating system, or it could implement an entirely different boot process such as network booting.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Operation of an IBM-compatible computer system can be completely changed by removing or inserting an adapter card (or a ROM chip) that contains a BIOS extension ROM.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] The motherboard BIOS typically contains code for initializing and bootstrapping integrated display and integrated storage.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] In addition, plug-in adapter cards such as SCSI, RAID, network interface cards, and video cards often include their own BIOS (e.g., Video BIOS), complementing or replacing the system BIOS code for the given component.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Even devices built into the motherboard can behave in this way; their option ROMs can be a part of the motherboard BIOS.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] An add-in card requires an option ROM if the card is not supported by the motherboard BIOS and the card needs to be initialized or made accessible through BIOS services before the operating system can be loaded (usually this means it is required in the boot process).
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] An additional advantage of ROM on some early PC systems (notably including the IBM PCjr) was that ROM was faster than main system RAM.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Option ROMs normally reside on adapter cards.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] The IBM PCjr is unique among PCs in having two ROM cartridge slots on the front.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Cartridges in these slots map into the same region of the upper memory area used for option ROMs, and the cartridges can contain option ROM modules that the BIOS would recognize.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] The cartridges can also contain other types of ROM modules, such as BASIC programs, that are handled differently.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] One PCjr cartridge can contain several ROM modules of different types, possibly stored together in one ROM chip.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] The 8086 and 8088 start at physical address FFFF0h.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] The 80286 starts at physical address FFFFF0h.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] The 80386 and later x86 processors start at physical address FFFFFFF0h.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] When the system is initialized, the first instruction of the BIOS appears at that address.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] If the system has just been powered up or the reset button was pressed ("cold boot"), the full power-on self-test (POST) is run.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] If Ctrl+Alt+Delete was pressed ("warm boot"), a special flag value stored in nonvolatile BIOS memory ("CMOS") tested by the BIOS allows bypass of the lengthy POST and memory detection.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] The POST identifies, tests and initializes system devices such as the CPU, chipset, RAM, motherboard, video card, keyboard, mouse, hard disk drive, optical disc drive and other hardware, including integrated peripherals.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Early IBM PCs had a routine in the POST that would download a program into RAM through the keyboard port and run it.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] This feature was intended for factory test or diagnostic purposes.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] After the motherboard BIOS completes its POST, most BIOS versions search for option ROM modules, also called BIOS extension ROMs, and execute them.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] The motherboard BIOS scans for extension ROMs in a portion of the "upper memory area" (the part of the x86 real-mode address space at and above address 0xA0000) and runs each ROM found, in order.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] To discover memory-mapped option ROMs, a BIOS implementation scans the real-mode address space from `0x0C0000` to `0x0F0000` on 2 KB (2,048 bytes) boundaries, looking for a two-byte ROM *signature*: 0x55 followed by 0xAA.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] In a valid expansion ROM, this signature is followed by a single byte indicating the number of 512-byte blocks the expansion ROM occupies in real memory, and the next byte is the option ROM's entry point (also known as its "entry offset").
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] If the ROM has a valid checksum, the BIOS transfers control to the entry address, which in a normal BIOS extension ROM should be the beginning of the extension's initialization routine.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] At this point, the extension ROM code takes over, typically testing and initializing the hardware it controls and registering interrupt vectors for use by post-boot applications.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] It may use BIOS services (including those provided by previously initialized option ROMs) to provide a user configuration interface, to display diagnostic information, or to do anything else that it requires.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] An option ROM should normally return to the BIOS after completing its initialization process.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Once (and if) an option ROM returns, the BIOS continues searching for more option ROMs, calling each as it is found, until the entire option ROM area in the memory space has been scanned.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] It is possible that an option ROM will not return to BIOS, pre-empting the BIOS's boot sequence altogether.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] After the POST completes and, in a BIOS that supports option ROMs, after the option ROM scan is completed and all detected ROM modules with valid checksums have been called, the BIOS calls interrupt 19h to start boot processing.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Post-boot, programs loaded can also call interrupt 19h to reboot the system, but they must be careful to disable interrupts and other asynchronous hardware processes that may interfere with the BIOS rebooting process, or else the system may hang or crash while it is rebooting.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] When interrupt 19h is called, the BIOS attempts to locate boot loader software on a "boot device", such as a hard disk, a floppy disk, CD, or DVD.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] It loads and executes the first boot software it finds, giving it control of the PC.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] The BIOS uses the boot devices set in Nonvolatile BIOS memory (CMOS), or, in the earliest PCs, DIP switches.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] The BIOS checks each device in order to see if it is bootable by attempting to load the first sector (boot sector).
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] If the sector cannot be read, the BIOS proceeds to the next device.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] If the sector is read successfully, some BIOSes will also check for the boot sector signature 0x55 0xAA in the last two bytes of the sector (which is 512 bytes long), before accepting a boot sector and considering the device bootable.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] When a bootable device is found, the BIOS transfers control to the loaded sector.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] The BIOS does not interpret the contents of the boot sector other than to possibly check for the boot sector signature in the last two bytes.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Interpretation of data structures like partition tables and BIOS Parameter Blocks is done by the boot program in the boot sector itself or by other programs loaded through the boot process.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] A non-disk device such as a network adapter attempts booting by a procedure that is defined by its option ROM or the equivalent integrated into the motherboard BIOS ROM.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] As such, option ROMs may also influence or supplant the boot process defined by the motherboard BIOS ROM.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] With the El Torito optical media boot standard, the optical drive actually emulates a 3.5" high-density floppy disk to the BIOS for boot purposes.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Reading the "first sector" of a CD-ROM or DVD-ROM is not a simply defined operation like it is on a floppy disk or a hard disk.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Furthermore, the complexity of the medium makes it difficult to write a useful boot program in one sector.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] The bootable virtual floppy disk can contain software that provides access to the optical medium in its native format.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] If an expansion ROM wishes to change the way the system boots (such as from a network device or a SCSI adapter) in a cooperative way, it can use the *BIOS Boot Specification* (BBS) API to register its ability to do so.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Once the expansion ROMs have registered using the BBS APIs, the user can select among the available boot options from within the BIOS's user interface.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] This is why most BBS compliant PC BIOS implementations will not allow the user to enter the BIOS's user interface until the expansion ROMs have finished executing and registering themselves with the BBS API.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Also, if an expansion ROM wishes to change the way the system boots unilaterally, it can simply hook interrupt 19h or other interrupts normally called from interrupt 19h, such as interrupt 13h, the BIOS disk service, to intercept the BIOS boot process.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Then it can replace the BIOS boot process with one of its own, or it can merely modify the boot sequence by inserting its own boot actions into it, by preventing the BIOS from detecting certain devices as bootable, or both.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Before the BIOS Boot Specification was promulgated, this was the only way for expansion ROMs to implement boot capability for devices not supported for booting by the native BIOS of the motherboard.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] The user can select the boot priority implemented by the BIOS.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] For example, most computers have a hard disk that is bootable, but sometimes there is a removable-media drive that has higher boot priority, so the user can cause a removable disk to be booted.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] In most modern BIOSes, the boot priority order can be configured by the user.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] The BIOS in an early PC also usually would only boot from the first floppy disk drive or the first hard disk drive, even if there were two drives installed.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] On the original IBM PC and XT, if no bootable disk was found, the BIOS would try to start ROM BASIC with the interrupt call to interrupt 18h.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Since few programs used BASIC in ROM, clone PC makers left it out; then a computer that failed to boot from a disk would display "No ROM BASIC" and halt (in response to interrupt 18h).
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Later computers would display a message like "No bootable disk found"; some would prompt for a disk to be inserted and a key to be pressed to retry the boot process.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] A modern BIOS may display nothing or may automatically enter the BIOS configuration utility when the boot process fails.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] The environment for the boot program is very simple: the CPU is in real mode and the general-purpose and segment registers are undefined, except SS, SP, CS, and DL.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] CS:IP always points to physical address `0x07C00`.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] What values CS and IP actually have is not well defined.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Because boot programs are always loaded at this fixed address, there is no need for a boot program to be relocatable.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] DL may contain the drive number, as used with interrupt 13h, of the boot device.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] SS:SP points to a valid stack that is presumably large enough to support hardware interrupts, but otherwise SS and SP are undefined.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] (A stack must be already set up in order for interrupts to be serviced, and interrupts must be enabled in order for the system timer-tick interrupt, which BIOS always uses at least to maintain the time-of-day count and which it initializes during POST, to be active and for the keyboard to work.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] At boot time, all BIOS services are available, and the memory below address `0x00400` contains the interrupt vector table.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] BIOS POST has initialized the system timers, interrupt controller(s), DMA controller(s), and other motherboard/chipset hardware as necessary to bring all BIOS services to ready status.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] DRAM refresh for all system DRAM in conventional memory and extended memory, but not necessarily expanded memory, has been set up and is running.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] The BIOS maintains a reserved block of system RAM at addresses `0x00400–0x004FF` with various parameters initialized during the POST.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] All memory at and above address `0x00500` can be used by the boot program; it may even overwrite itself.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] The BIOS ROM is customized to the particular manufacturer's hardware, allowing low-level services (such as reading a keystroke or writing a sector of data to diskette) to be provided in a standardized way to programs, including operating systems.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] For example, an IBM PC might have either a monochrome or a color display adapter (using different display memory addresses and hardware), but a single, standard, BIOS system call may be invoked to display a character at a specified position on the screen in text mode or graphics mode.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] The BIOS provides a small library of basic input/output functions to operate peripherals (such as the keyboard, rudimentary text and graphics display functions and so forth).
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Operating systems and executive software that are designed to supersede this basic firmware functionality provide replacement software interfaces to application software.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Applications can also provide these services to themselves.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] This began even in the 1980s under MS-DOS, when programmers observed that using the BIOS video services for graphics display were very slow.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] To increase the speed of screen output, many programs bypassed the BIOS and programmed the video display hardware directly.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Other graphics programmers, particularly but not exclusively in the demoscene, observed that there were technical capabilities of the PC display adapters that were not supported by the IBM BIOS and could not be taken advantage of without circumventing it.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Since the AT-compatible BIOS ran in Intel real mode, operating systems that ran in protected mode on 286 and later processors required hardware device drivers compatible with protected mode operation to replace BIOS services.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Modern operating systems, such as Windows and Linux, use the BIOS interrupt calls only during the booting process.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Before the operating system's first graphical screen is displayed, input and output are typically handled through BIOS.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] A boot menu such as the textual menu of Windows, which allows users to choose an operating system to boot, to boot into the safe mode, or to use the last known good configuration, is displayed through BIOS and receives keyboard input through BIOS.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Many modern PCs can still boot and run legacy operating systems such as MS-DOS or DR-DOS that rely heavily on BIOS for their console and disk I/O, providing that the system has a BIOS, or a CSM-capable UEFI firmware.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Intel processors have reprogrammable microcode since the P6 microarchitecture.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] AMD processors have reprogrammable microcode since the K7 microarchitecture.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] The BIOS contains patches to the processor microcode that fix errors in the initial processor microcode; microcode is loaded into processor's SRAM so reprogramming is not persistent, thus loading of microcode updates is performed each time the system is powered up.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Without reprogrammable microcode, an expensive processor swap would be required; for example, the Pentium FDIV bug became an expensive fiasco for Intel as it required a product recall because the original Pentium processor's defective microcode could not be reprogrammed.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Operating systems can also update the microcode.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Some BIOSes contain a software licensing description table (SLIC), a digital signature placed inside the BIOS by the original equipment manufacturer (OEM), for example Dell.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] The SLIC is inserted into the ACPI data table and contains no active code.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Computer manufacturers that distribute OEM versions of Microsoft Windows and Microsoft application software can use the SLIC to authenticate licensing to the OEM Windows Installation disk and system recovery disc containing Windows software.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Systems with a SLIC can be preactivated with an OEM product key, and they verify an XML formatted OEM certificate against the SLIC in the BIOS as a means of self-activating (see System Locked Preinstallation, SLP).
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] If a user performs a fresh install of Windows, they will need to have possession of both the OEM key (either SLP or COA) and the digital certificate for their SLIC in order to bypass activation.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] This can be achieved if the user performs a restore using a pre-customised image provided by the OEM.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Power users can copy the necessary certificate files from the OEM image, decode the SLP product key, then perform SLP activation manually.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Some BIOS implementations allow overclocking, an action in which the CPU is adjusted to a higher clock rate than its manufacturer rating for guaranteed capability.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Overclocking may, however, seriously compromise system reliability in insufficiently cooled computers and generally shorten component lifespan.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Overclocking, when incorrectly performed, may also cause components to overheat so quickly that they mechanically destroy themselves.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Some older operating systems, for example MS-DOS, rely on the BIOS to carry out most input/output tasks within the PC.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Calling real mode BIOS services directly is inefficient for protected mode (and long mode) operating systems.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] BIOS interrupt calls are not used by modern multitasking operating systems after they initially load.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] In the 1990s, BIOS provided some protected mode interfaces for Microsoft Windows and Unix-like operating systems, such as Advanced Power Management (APM), Plug and Play BIOS, Desktop Management Interface (DMI), VESA BIOS Extensions (VBE), e820 and MultiProcessor Specification (MPS).
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Starting from the year 2000, most BIOSes provide ACPI, SMBIOS, VBE and e820 interfaces for modern operating systems.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] After operating systems load, the System Management Mode code is still running in SMRAM.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Since 2010, BIOS technology is in a transitional process toward UEFI.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Historically, the BIOS in the IBM PC and XT had no built-in user interface.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] The BIOS versions in earlier PCs (XT-class) were not software configurable; instead, users set the options via DIP switches on the motherboard.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Later computers, including most IBM-compatibles with 80286 CPUs, had a battery-backed nonvolatile BIOS memory (CMOS RAM chip) that held BIOS settings.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] These settings, such as video-adapter type, memory size, and hard-disk parameters, could only be configured by running a configuration program from a disk, not built into the ROM.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] A special "reference diskette" was inserted in an IBM AT to configure settings such as memory size.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Early BIOS versions did not have passwords or boot-device selection options.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] The BIOS was hard-coded to boot from the first floppy drive, or, if that failed, the first hard disk.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Access control in early AT-class machines was by a physical keylock switch (which was not hard to defeat if the computer case could be opened).
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Anyone who could switch on the computer could boot it.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Later, 386-class computers started integrating the BIOS setup utility in the ROM itself, alongside the BIOS code; these computers usually boot into the BIOS setup utility if a certain key or key combination is pressed, otherwise the BIOS POST and boot process are executed.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] A modern BIOS setup utility has a text user interface (TUI) or graphical user interface (GUI) accessed by pressing a certain key on the keyboard when the PC starts.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Usually, the key is advertised for short time during the early startup, for example "Press DEL to enter Setup".
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] The actual key depends on specific hardware.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] The settings key is most often Delete (Acer, ASRock, Asus PC, ECS, Gigabyte, MSI, Zotac) and F2 (Asus motherboard, Dell, Lenovo laptop, Origin PC, Samsung, Toshiba), but it can also be F1 (Lenovo desktop) and F10 (HP).
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] A modern BIOS setup screen often features a **PC Health Status** or a **Hardware Monitoring** tab, which directly interfaces with a Hardware Monitor chip of the mainboard.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] This makes it possible to monitor CPU and chassis temperature, the voltage provided by the power supply unit, as well as monitor and control the speed of the fans connected to the motherboard.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Some operating systems, like NetBSD with envsys and OpenBSD with sysctl hw.sensors, feature integrated interfacing with hardware monitors.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] However, in some circumstances, the BIOS also provides the underlying information about hardware monitoring through ACPI, in which case, the operating system may be using ACPI to perform hardware monitoring.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] In modern PCs the BIOS is stored in rewritable EEPROM or NOR flash memory, allowing the contents to be replaced and modified.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] This rewriting of the contents is sometimes termed *flashing.* It can be done by a special program, usually provided by the system's manufacturer, or at POST, with a BIOS image in a hard drive or USB flash drive.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] A file containing such contents is sometimes termed "a BIOS image".
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] A BIOS might be reflashed in order to upgrade to a newer version to fix bugs or provide improved performance or to support newer hardware.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Some computers also support updating the BIOS via an update floppy disk or a special partition on the hard drive.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] The original IBM PC BIOS (and cassette BASIC) was stored on mask-programmed read-only memory (ROM) chips in sockets on the motherboard.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] ROMs could be replaced, but not altered, by users.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] To allow for updates, many compatible computers used re-programmable BIOS memory devices such as EPROM, EEPROM and later flash memory (usually NOR flash) devices.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] According to Robert Braver, the president of the BIOS manufacturer Micro Firmware, **Flash BIOS** chips became common around 1995 because the electrically erasable PROM (EEPROM) chips are cheaper and easier to program than standard ultraviolet erasable PROM (EPROM) chips.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Flash chips are programmed (and re-programmed) in-circuit, while EPROM chips need to be removed from the motherboard for re-programming.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] BIOS versions are upgraded to take advantage of newer versions of hardware and to correct bugs in previous revisions of BIOSes.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Beginning with the IBM AT, PCs supported a hardware clock settable through BIOS.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] It had a century bit which allowed for manually changing the century when the year 2000 happened.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Most BIOS revisions created in 1995 and nearly all BIOS revisions in 1997 supported the year 2000 by setting the century bit automatically when the clock rolled past midnight, 31 December 1999.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] The first flash chips were attached to the ISA bus.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Starting in 1998, the BIOS flash moved to the LPC bus, following a new standard implementation known as "firmware hub" (FWH).
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] In 2005, the BIOS flash memory moved to the SPI bus.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] The size of the BIOS, and the capacity of the ROM, EEPROM, or other media it may be stored on, has increased over time as new features have been added to the code; BIOS versions now exist with sizes up to 32 megabytes.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] For contrast, the original IBM PC BIOS was contained in an 8 KB mask ROM.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Some modern motherboards are including even bigger NAND flash memory ICs on board which are capable of storing whole compact operating systems, such as some Linux distributions.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] For example, some ASUS notebooks included Splashtop OS embedded into their NAND flash memory ICs.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] However, the idea of including an operating system along with BIOS in the ROM of a PC is not new; in the 1980s, Microsoft offered a ROM option for MS-DOS, and it was included in the ROMs of some PC clones such as the Tandy 1000 HX.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Another type of firmware chip was found on the IBM PC AT and early compatibles.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] In the AT, the keyboard interface was controlled by a microcontroller with its own programmable memory.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] On the IBM AT, that was a 40-pin socketed device, while some manufacturers used an EPROM version of this chip which resembled an EPROM.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] This controller was also assigned the A20 gate function to manage memory above the one-megabyte range; occasionally an upgrade of this "keyboard BIOS" was necessary to take advantage of software that could use upper memory.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] The BIOS may contain components such as the Memory Reference Code (MRC), which is responsible for the memory initialization (e.g.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Modern BIOS includes Intel Management Engine or AMD Platform Security Processor firmware.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] IBM published full listings of the BIOSes for its original PC, PC XT, PC AT, and other contemporary PC models, in an appendix of the *IBM PC Technical Reference Manual* for each machine type.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] A benefit of the publication of the BIOS listings is that users could see exactly what the BIOS does and how it does it.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] However, those BIOSes were still copyright by IBM, so they could not be used by other manufacturers.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] In March 1983, Compaq released its Compaq Portable, which included a clean-room engineered BIOS.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] This made Compaq became the first company that cloned an IBM PC successfully.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] However, Compaq did not offer their BIOS to other computer manufacturers.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] In May 1984, Phoenix Software Associates released its first ROM-BIOS.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] This BIOS enabled OEMs to build essentially fully compatible clones without having to reverse-engineer the IBM PC BIOS themselves, as Compaq had done for the Portable; it also helped fuel the growth in the PC-compatibles industry and sales of non-IBM versions of DOS.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] The first American Megatrends (AMI) BIOS was released in 1986.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] New standards grafted onto the BIOS are usually without complete public documentation or any BIOS listings.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] As a result, it is not as easy to learn the intimate details about the many non-IBM additions to BIOS as about the core BIOS services.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Many PC motherboard suppliers licensed the BIOS "core" and toolkit from a commercial third party, known as an "independent BIOS vendor" or IBV.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] The motherboard manufacturer then customized this BIOS to suit its own hardware.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] For this reason, updated BIOSes are normally obtained directly from the motherboard manufacturer.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Major IBVs included American Megatrends (AMI), Insyde Software, Phoenix Technologies, and Byosoft.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Microid Research and Award Software were acquired by Phoenix Technologies in 1998; Phoenix later phased out the Award brand name (although Award Software is still credited in AwardBIOS versions until 2001–2002, and AWRDACPI is still credited in Phoenix UEFI firmwares until late 2012).
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] General Software, which was also acquired by Phoenix in 2007, sold BIOS for embedded systems based on Intel processors.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] SeaBIOS is an open-source BIOS implementation.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] The open-source community increased their effort to develop a replacement for proprietary BIOSes and their future incarnations with open-sourced counterparts.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Open Firmware was an early attempt to make an open specification for boot firmware.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] It was initially endorsed by IEEE in its *IEEE 1275-1994* standard but was withdrawn in 2005.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Later examples include the OpenBIOS, coreboot and libreboot projects.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] AMD provided product specifications for some chipsets using coreboot, and Google is sponsoring the project.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Motherboard manufacturer Tyan offers coreboot next to the standard BIOS with their Opteron line of motherboards.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] EEPROM and flash memory chips are advantageous because they can be easily updated by the user; it is customary for hardware manufacturers to issue BIOS updates to upgrade their products, improve compatibility and remove bugs.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] However, this advantage had the risk that an improperly executed or aborted BIOS update could render the computer or device unusable.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] To avoid these situations, more recent BIOSes use a "boot block"; a portion of the BIOS which runs first and must be updated separately.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] This code verifies if the rest of the BIOS is intact (using hash checksums or other methods) before transferring control to it.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] If the boot block detects any corruption in the main BIOS, it will typically warn the user that a recovery process must be initiated by booting from removable media (floppy, CD or USB flash drive) so the user can try flashing the BIOS again.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Some motherboards have a *backup* BIOS (sometimes referred as DualBIOS) to recover from BIOS corruptions, and they use a special PLC to do BIOS recovery from BIOS corruptions.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] There are at least five known viruses that attack the BIOS, two of which were for demonstration purposes.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] The first one found in the wild was *Mebromi*, targeting Chinese users.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] The first BIOS virus was BIOS Meningitis, which instead of erasing BIOS chips it infected them.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] BIOS Meningitis was relatively harmless, compared to a virus like CIH.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] The second BIOS virus was CIH, also known as the "Chernobyl Virus", which was able to erase flash ROM BIOS content on compatible chipsets.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] CIH appeared in mid-1998 and became active in April 1999.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Often, infected computers could no longer boot, and people had to remove the flash ROM IC from the motherboard and reprogram it.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] CIH targeted the then-widespread Intel i430TX motherboard chipset and took advantage of the fact that the Windows 9x operating systems, also widespread at the time, allowed direct hardware access to all programs.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Modern systems are not vulnerable to CIH because of a variety of chipsets being used which are incompatible with the Intel i430TX chipset, and also other flash ROM IC types.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] There is also extra protection from accidental BIOS rewrites in the form of boot blocks which are protected from accidental overwrite or dual BIOS equipped systems which may, in the event of a crash, use a backup BIOS.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Also, all modern operating systems such as FreeBSD, Linux, macOS, Windows NT-based Windows OS like Windows 2000, Windows XP and newer, do not allow user-mode programs to have direct hardware access using a hardware abstraction layer.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] As a result, as of 2008, CIH has become essentially harmless, at worst causing annoyance by infecting executable files and triggering antivirus software.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Other BIOS viruses remain possible, however; since most Windows home users without Windows Vista/7's UAC run all applications with administrative privileges, a modern CIH-like virus could in principle still gain access to hardware without first using an exploit.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] The operating system OpenBSD prevents all users from having this access and the grsecurity patch for the Linux kernel also prevents this direct hardware access by default, the difference being an attacker requiring a much more difficult kernel level exploit or reboot of the machine.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] The third BIOS virus was a technique presented by John Heasman, principal security consultant for UK-based Next-Generation Security Software.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] In 2006, at the Black Hat Security Conference, he showed how to elevate privileges and read physical memory, using malicious procedures that replaced normal ACPI functions stored in flash memory.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] The fourth BIOS virus was a technique called "Persistent BIOS infection." It appeared in 2009 at the CanSecWest Security Conference in Vancouver, and at the SyScan Security Conference in Singapore.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Researchers Anibal Sacco and Alfredo Ortega, from Core Security Technologies, demonstrated how to insert malicious code into the decompression routines in the BIOS, allowing for nearly full control of the PC at start-up, even before the operating system is booted.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] The proof-of-concept does not exploit a flaw in the BIOS implementation, but only involves the normal BIOS flashing procedures.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Thus, it requires physical access to the machine, or for the user to be root.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Despite these requirements, Ortega underlined the profound implications of his and Sacco's discovery: "We can patch a driver to drop a fully working rootkit.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Mebromi is a trojan which targets computers with AwardBIOS, Microsoft Windows, and antivirus software from two Chinese companies: Rising Antivirus and Jiangmin KV Antivirus.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Mebromi installs a rootkit which infects the Master boot record.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] In a December 2013 interview with *60 Minutes*, Deborah Plunkett, Information Assurance Director for the US National Security Agency claimed the NSA had uncovered and thwarted a possible BIOS attack by a foreign nation state, targeting the US financial system.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] The program cited anonymous sources alleging it was a Chinese plot.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] However follow-up articles in *The Guardian,* *The Atlantic,* *Wired* and *The Register* refuted the NSA's claims.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Newer Intel platforms have Intel Boot Guard (IBG) technology enabled, this technology will check the BIOS digital signature at startup, and the IBG public key is fused into the PCH.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Unified Extensible Firmware Interface (UEFI) supplements the BIOS in many new machines.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Initially written for the Intel Itanium architecture, UEFI is now available for x86 and Arm platforms; the specification development is driven by the Unified EFI Forum, an industry special interest group.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] EFI booting has been supported in only Microsoft Windows versions supporting GPT, the Linux kernel 2.6.1 and later, and macOS on Intel-based Macs.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] As of 2014, new PC hardware predominantly ships with UEFI firmware.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] The architecture of the rootkit safeguard can also prevent the system from running the user's own software changes, which makes UEFI controversial as a legacy BIOS replacement in the open hardware community.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] UEFI is required for devices shipping with Windows 8 and above.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Likewise, Windows 11 requires UEFI to boot, with the exception of IoT Enterprise editions of Windows 11.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] After the popularity of UEFI in 2010s, the older BIOS that supported BIOS interrupt calls was renamed to "legacy BIOS".
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Other alternatives to the functionality of the "Legacy BIOS" in the x86 world include coreboot and libreboot.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Some servers and workstations use a platform-independent Open Firmware (IEEE-1275) based on the Forth programming language; it is included with Sun's SPARC computers, IBM's RS/6000 line, and other PowerPC systems such as the CHRP motherboards, along with the x86-based OLPC XO-1.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] As of at least 2015, Apple has removed legacy BIOS support from the UEFI monitor in Intel-based Macs.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] As such, the BIOS utility no longer supports the legacy option, and prints "Legacy mode not supported on this system".
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] In 2017, Intel announced that it would remove legacy BIOS support by 2020.
[src:dual-in-line-package/bios] Since 2019, new Intel platform OEM PCs no longer support the legacy option.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] In microelectronics, a **dual in-line package** (**DIP** or **DIL**) is an electronic component package with a rectangular housing and two parallel rows of electrical connecting pins.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] The package may be through-hole mounted to a printed circuit board (PCB) or inserted in a socket.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] The dual-inline format was invented by Don Forbes, Rex Rice and Bryant Rogers at Fairchild R&D in 1964, when the restricted number of leads available on circular transistor-style packages became a limitation in the use of integrated circuits.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] Increasingly complex circuits required more signal and power supply leads (as observed in Rent's rule); eventually microprocessors and similar complex devices required more leads than could be put on a DIP package, leading to development of higher-density chip carriers.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] Furthermore, square and rectangular packages made it easier to route printed-circuit traces beneath the packages.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] A DIP is usually referred to as a **DIP*n***, where *n* is the total number of pins, and sometimes appended with the row-to-row package width "N" for narrow (0.3") or "W" for wide (0.6").
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] For example, a microcircuit package with two rows of seven vertical leads would be a DIP14 or DIP14N.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] The photograph at the upper right shows three DIP14 ICs.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] Common packages have as few as four and as many as 64 leads.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] Many analog and digital integrated circuit types are available in DIP packages, as are arrays of transistors, switches, light emitting diodes, and resistors.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] DIP plugs for ribbon cables can be used with standard IC sockets.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] DIP packages are usually made from an opaque molded epoxy plastic pressed around a tin-, silver-, or gold-plated lead frame that supports the device die and provides connection pins.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] Some types of IC are made in ceramic DIP packages, where high temperature or high reliability is required, or where the device has an optical window to the interior of the package.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] Most DIP packages are secured to a PCB by inserting the pins through holes in the board and soldering them in place.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] Where replacement of the parts is necessary, such as in test fixtures or where programmable devices must be removed for changes, a DIP socket is used.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] Some sockets include a zero insertion force (ZIF) mechanism.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] Variations of the DIP package include those with only a single row of pins, e.g. a resistor array, possibly including a heat sink tab in place of the second row of pins, and types with four rows of pins, two rows, staggered, on each side of the package.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] DIP packages have been mostly displaced by surface-mount package types, which avoid the expense of drilling holes in a PCB and which allow higher density of interconnections.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] DIPs are commonly used for integrated circuits (ICs).
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] Other devices in DIP packages include resistor networks, DIP switches, LED segmented and bar graph displays, and electromechanical relays.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] DIP connector plugs for ribbon cables are common in computers and other electronic equipment.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] Dallas Semiconductor manufactured integrated DIP real-time clock (RTC) modules which contained an IC chip and a non-replaceable 10-year lithium battery.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] DIP header blocks onto which discrete components could be soldered were used where groups of components needed to be easily removed, for configuration changes, optional features or calibration.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] The original dual-in-line package was invented by Bryant "Buck" Rogers in 1964 while working for Fairchild Semiconductor.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] The first devices had 14 pins and looked much like they do today.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] The rectangular shape allowed integrated circuits to be packaged more densely than previous round packages.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] DIP packages were still large with respect to the integrated circuits within them.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] By the end of the 20th century, surface-mount packages allowed further reduction in the size and weight of systems.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] DIP chips are still popular for circuit prototyping on a breadboard because of how easily they can be inserted and used there.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] DIPs were the mainstream of the microelectronics industry in the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] Through the 1990s, devices with fewer than 20 leads were typically manufactured in a DIP format in addition to the newer formats.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] Since about 2000, newer devices are often unavailable in the DIP format.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] DIPs can be mounted either by through-hole soldering or in sockets.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] Sockets allow easy replacement of a device and eliminates the risk of damage from overheating during soldering.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] Generally sockets were used for high-value or large ICs, which cost much more than the socket.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] Where devices would be frequently inserted and removed, such as in test equipment or EPROM programmers, a zero insertion force socket would be used.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] DIPs are also used with breadboards, a temporary mounting arrangement for education, design development or device testing.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] Some hobbyists, for one-off construction or permanent prototyping, use point-to-point wiring with DIPs, and their appearance when physically inverted as part of this method inspires the informal term "dead bug style" for the method.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] The body (housing) of a DIP containing an IC chip is usually made from molded plastic or ceramic.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] The hermetic nature of a ceramic housing is preferred for extremely high reliability devices.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] However, the vast majority of DIPs are manufactured via a thermoset molding process in which an epoxy mold compound is heated and transferred under pressure to encapsulate the device.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] Typical cure cycles for the resins are less than 2 minutes and a single cycle may produce hundreds of devices.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] The leads emerge from the longer sides of the package along the seam, parallel to the top and bottom planes of the package, and are bent downward approximately 90 degrees (or slightly less, leaving them angled slightly outward from the centerline of the package body).
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] However, contaminants are usually still kept out well enough that the device can operate reliably for decades with reasonable care in a controlled environment.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] Inside the package, the lower half has the leads embedded, and at the center of the package is a rectangular space, chamber, or void into which the IC die is cemented.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] The leads of the package extend diagonally inside the package from their positions of emergence along the periphery to points along a rectangular perimeter surrounding the die, tapering as they go to become fine contacts at the die.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] Ultra-fine bond wires (barely visible to the naked human eye) are welded between these die periphery contacts and bond pads on the die itself, connecting one lead to each bond pad, and making the final connection between the microcircuits and the external DIP leads.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] The bond wires are not usually taut but loop upward slightly to allow slack for thermal expansion and contraction of the materials; if a single bond wire breaks or detaches, the entire IC may become useless.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] The top of the package covers all of this delicate assemblage without crushing the bond wires, protecting it from contamination by foreign materials.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] Even for a very small die with many bond pads (e.g. a chip with 15 inverters, requiring 32 leads), a wider DIP would still be required to accommodate the radiating leads internally.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] This is one of the reasons that four-sided and multiple rowed packages, such as PGAs, were introduced (around the early 1980s).
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] A large DIP package (such as the DIP64 used for the Motorola 68000 CPU) has long leads inside the package between pins and the die, making such a package unsuitable for high speed devices.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] Some other types of DIP devices are built very differently.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] Most of these have molded plastic housings and straight leads or leads that extend directly out of the bottom of the package.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] For some, LED displays particularly, the housing is usually a hollow plastic box with the bottom/back open, filled (around the contained electronic components) with a hard translucent epoxy material from which the leads emerge.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] Others, such as DIP switches, are composed of two (or more) plastic housing parts snapped, welded, or glued together around a set of contacts and tiny mechanical parts, with the leads emerging through molded-in holes or notches in the plastic.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] EPROMs were sold in ceramic DIPs manufactured with a circular window of clear quartz over the chip die to allow the part to be erased by ultraviolet light.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] Often, the same chips were also sold in less expensive windowless PDIP or CERDIP packages as one-time programmable (OTP) versions.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] Windowed and windowless packages were also used for microcontrollers, and other devices, containing EPROM memory.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] Windowed CERDIP-packaged EPROMs were used for the BIOS ROM of many early IBM PC clones with an adhesive label covering the window to prevent inadvertent erasure through exposure to ambient light.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] Molded plastic DIPs are much lower in cost than ceramic packages; one 1979 study showed that a plastic 14 pin DIP cost around US$0.063 and a ceramic package cost US$0.82.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] A **single in-line package** (**SIP** or **SIL package**) has one row of connecting pins.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] It is not as popular as the DIP, but has been used for packaging RAM chips and multiple resistors with a common pin.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] As compared to DIPs with a typical maximum pin count of 64, SIPs have a typical maximum pin count of 24 with lower package costs.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] One variant of the single in-line package uses part of the lead frame for a heat sink tab.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] This multi-leaded power package is useful for such applications as audio power amplifiers, for example.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] The QIP, sometimes called a *QIL package*, has the same dimensions as a DIL package, but the leads on each side are bent into an alternating zigzag configuration so as to fit four lines of solder pads (instead of two with a DIL).
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] QIL also increased the possibility of running a copper track between 2 solder pads.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] This was very handy on the then standard single sided single layer PCBs.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] Commonly found DIP packages that conform to JEDEC standards use an inter-lead spacing (lead pitch) of 0.1 inches (2.54 mm) (JEDEC MS-001BA).
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] Row spacing varies depending on lead counts, with 0.3 in.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] Less common standardized row spacings include 0.4 inch (10.16 mm) (JEDEC MS-010) and 0.9 inch (22.86 mm), as well as a row spacing of 0.3 inch, 0.6 inch or 0.75 inch with a 0.07 inch (1.778 mm) lead pitch.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] The former Soviet Union and Eastern bloc countries used similar packages, but with a metric pin-to-pin spacing of 2.5 mm rather than 0.1 inches (2.54 mm).
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] For 0.3 inch wide rows, typical lead counts are 8, 14, 16, and 20; less common are 4, 6, 18, 24, and 28 lead counts.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] To have an even number of leads some DIPs have unused not connected (NC) leads to the internal chip, or are duplicated, e.g. two ground pins.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] For 0.6 inch rows, typical lead counts are 24, 28, 32, and 40; less common are 36, 42, 48, 52, and 64 lead counts.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] For 0.9 inch rows, typical lead counts are 50 and 64 leads.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] Some microprocessors, such as the Motorola 68000 and Zilog Z180, used lead counts of 64; this is typically the maximum number of leads for a DIP package.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] As shown in the diagram, leads are numbered consecutively from Pin 1.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] When the identifying notch in the package is at the top, Pin 1 is the top left corner of the device.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] Sometimes Pin 1 is identified with an indent or paint dot mark.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] For example, for a 14-lead DIP, with the notch at the top, the left leads are numbered from 1 to 7 (top to bottom) and the right row of leads are numbered 8 to 14 (bottom to top).
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] Leads are skipped on some DIP devices (e.g. segmented LED displays, relays, or devices that replace leads with a heat sink fin).
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] The remaining leads are numbered as if all positions had leads.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] In addition to providing for human visual identification of the orientation of the package, the notch allows automated chip-insertion machinery to confirm correct orientation of the chip by mechanical sensing.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] The SOJ (Small Outline J-lead) and other SMT packages with "SOP" (for "Small Outline Package") in their names can be considered further relatives of the DIP, their original ancestor.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] SOIC packages tend to have half the pitch of DIP, and SOP are half that, a fourth of DIP.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] Pin grid array (PGA) packages may be considered to have evolved from the DIP.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] PGAs with the same 0.1 inches (2.54 mm) pin centers as most DIPs were popular for microprocessors from the early to mid-1980s through the 1990s.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] Owners of personal computers containing Intel 80286 through P5 Pentium processors may be most familiar with these PGA packages, which were often inserted into ZIF sockets on motherboards.
[src:dual-in-line-package/dual-in-line-package] The similarity is such that a PGA socket may be physically compatible with some DIP devices, though the converse is rarely true.
